afe", "comment": "sp", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Karate_at_the_2019_Pan_American_Games"}
{"title_page": "Canada Emergency Business Account", "text_new": "{{Underlinked|date=April 2020}}\n\nThe '''Canadian Emergency Business Account''' ('''CEBA''') is a Canadian support program created by the [[Government of Canada]].<ref name=\"gm3br\">{{cite news |title=The three bridges Canada needs to get us across the economic chasm |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/opinion/editorials/article-the-three-bridges-canada-needs-to-get-us-across-the-economic-chasm/ |publisher=The Globe and Mail Inc |date=13 April 2020}}</ref> The program was launched on 11 April 2020, upon passage of Bill C-XXX, for Canadian businesses facing mounting business expenses like rent due to the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Canada|2020 coronavirus pandemic]].\n\nThe CEBA was budgeted for $25 billion. It offered interest-free loans of up to $40,000. The first payment was due at the beginning  of 2023, and $10,000 of the loan would be forgiven if the rest is repaid. The size of the loans could be increased, along with the amount forgivable. The due date could also be moved into 2024 if need be.<ref name=\"gm3br\"/>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Government in Canada]]\n[[Category:Canadian society]]\n[[Category:Social programs]]\n[[Category:Social security in Canada]]\n[[Category:Unemployment benefits]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Canada]]\n[[Category:National responses to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n\n\n{{Canada-stub}}\n{{COVID-19-stub}}\n", "text_old": "\n\nThe '''Canadian Emergency Business Account''' ('''CEBA''') is a Canadian support program created by the [[Government of Canada]].<ref name=\"gm3br\">{{cite news |title=The three bridges Canada needs to get us across the economic chasm |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/opinion/editorials/article-the-three-bridges-canada-needs-to-get-us-across-the-economic-chasm/ |publisher=The Globe and Mail Inc |date=13 April 2020}}</ref> The program was launched on 11 April 2020, upon passage of Bill C-XXX, for Canadian businesses facing mounting business expenses like rent due to the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Canada|2020 coronavirus pandemic]].\n\nThe CEBA was budgeted for $25 billion. It offered interest-free loans of up to $40,000. The first payment was due at the beginning  of 2023, and $10,000 of the loan would be forgiven if the rest is repaid. The size of the loans could be increased, along with the amount forgivable. The due date could also be moved into 2024 if need be.<ref name=\"gm3br\"/>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Government in Canada]]\n[[Category:Canadian society]]\n[[Category:Social programs]]\n[[Category:Social security in Canada]]\n[[Category:Unemployment benefits]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Canada]]\n[[Category:National responses to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n\n\n{{Canada-stub}}\n{{COVID-19-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Joeykai", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:clean up, addedunderlinkedtag", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Canada_Emergency_Business_Account"}
{"title_page": "Peggy Cooper Cafritz", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name = Peggy Cooper Cafritz\n| image = \n| alt = \n| caption = \n| birth_name = Pearl Alice Cooper\n| birth_date = {{birth date|1947|4|07|mf=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Mobile, Alabama]], U.S.\n| death_date = {{Death date and age|2018|02|18|1947|04|07}}\n| death_place = [[Washington, D.C.]], U.S.\n| other_names = Peggy Cooper\n| occupation = [[Art collector]], educator, [[civil rights activist]], [[philanthropy|philanthropist]]\n| alma_mater = [[Saint Mary's College (Indiana)|St Mary's College]],<br/>[[George Washington University]]\n| years_active = 1960s\u20132018\n| spouse = {{marriage|Conrad Cafritz|1981|1998}}\n| children = 3 \n}}\n'''Peggy Cooper Cafritz''' (born '''Pearl Alice Cooper'''; April 7, 1947 \u2013 February 18, 2018) was an American [[art collector]], educator, [[civil rights activist]], [[Philanthropy|philanthropist]] and socialite.<ref name=\"Bernstein 2018\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/obituaries/peggy-coopercafritz-grande-dame-of-the-washington-arts-and-education-scene-dies-at-70/2018/02/18/0f6bb948-14c1-11e8-92c9-376b4fe57ff7_story.html|title=Peggy Cooper Cafritz, grande dame of the Washington arts and education scene, dies at 70|last=Bernstein|first=Adam|date=2018-02-18|work=Washington Post|access-date=2018-02-18|issn=0190-8286|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180218185553/https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/obituaries/peggy-coopercafritz-grande-dame-of-the-washington-arts-and-education-scene-dies-at-70/2018/02/18/0f6bb948-14c1-11e8-92c9-376b4fe57ff7_story.html|archivedate=2018-02-18}}</ref><ref name=\"Rosen\">{{cite news |last1=Rosen |first1=Miss |title=The art world remembers the force of nature who we lost too soon |url=http://www.dazeddigital.com/art-photography/article/39708/1/art-world-remembers-peggy-cooper-cafritz-the-force-of-nature-who-lost-too-soon |accessdate=6 April 2019 |work=Dazed |date=18 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nBorn Pearl Alice Cooper, Peggy Cafritz belonged to one of the wealthiest African American families in [[Mobile, Alabama]]. Her childhood nickname \"Peggy\" was eventually legally changed to be her real name. The Cooper family gained their wealth through Peggy's father who worked for the family business of insurance and mortuary services. Her parents were socially acquainted with famous jazz musician [[Duke Ellington]], namesake of the [[Duke Ellington School of the Arts]] which Cafritz would go on to co-found.<ref name= aisfor>Blum, Justin (May 21, 2002). \"A Is for Activist: D.C. Schools President Peggy Cooper Cafritz Raises Her Hand\". ''The Washington Post''. p. C1.</ref>\n\nAs a child, Cooper attended a segregated Catholic elementary school for black children and was raised Catholic.<ref name=\"USA\" /> The racism she experienced would shape her world view. \n\nThe summer after graduating from high school, Cafritz and her friends tried to be served at a [[drive-in restaurant]]; the [[Civil Rights Act of 1964]] had recently been passed, forbidding racial discrimination in restaurants. When Cafritz and her friends buzzed for service, several white teenage boys approached their car, spat on them, threw soda through their car window, and jumped on the hood of the car. Two police officers watched from nearby but did nothing.<ref name= aisfor/>\n\nIn 1964, during the [[civil rights movement]], Cafritz graduated from [[Saint Mary's College (Indiana)|St Mary's College]] in Indiana and moved to [[Washington, D.C.]] to attend [[George Washington University]] where she organized the [[Black Students Union|Black Student Union]] and worked on the integration of fraternities and sororities in 1968.<ref name=\"USA\"/> She received her law degree from George Washington University in 1971.<ref name=\"USA\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/2018/02/18/activist-peggy-cooper-cafritz-who-helped-build-model-public-education-dies-70/349617002/|title=Activist Peggy Cooper Cafritz, who helped build a model for public education, dies at 70|work=USA TODAY|access-date=2018-02-19|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180219081327/https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/2018/02/18/activist-peggy-cooper-cafritz-who-helped-build-model-public-education-dies-70/349617002/|archivedate=2018-02-19}}</ref> In the 1970s she was the youngest fellow of [[Woodrow Wilson International Center for Scholars]].<ref name=\"Bernstein 2018\" />\n\n==Career==\nCafritz wanted to bring the money of the white people and the power of the black people in Washington, D.C., together in unity.<ref name=\"Bernstein 2018\" />\n\nIn 1968, Cafritz she bused in inner-city students to attend a black arts festival that the organized.<ref name=\"Bernstein 2018\"/> Afterwards she and choreographer [[Mike Malone (choreographer)|Mike Malone]] created a summer arts workshop for at-risk high school children. This program became the magnet school [[Duke Ellington School of the Arts]], which she and Malone founded in 1974 and which they modeled after New York City's [[High School of Performing Arts]].<ref name=\"Bernstein 2018\"/> Their goal was to start an arts-education program for local children who had showed promise but had no outlet to demonstrate their potential.<ref name= aisfor/> Ellington was the only public high school in Washington, D.C., to train students with a curriculum in both academics and intensive professional arts training.{{citation needed|date=February 2018}} Ellington alumni include [[Dave Chappelle]], [[Denyce Graves]], [[Hank Willis Thomas]] and [[Meshell Ndegeocello]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/10/04/arts/design/hank-willis-thomas-art.html|title=Artist Sews Together Sports and Geopolitics|last=Vecsey|first=George|date=2017-10-04|work=The New York Times|access-date=2018-02-19|issn=0362-4331|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171004095704/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/10/04/arts/design/hank-willis-thomas-art.html|archivedate=2017-10-04}}</ref><ref name=\"Valentine 2018\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/entertainment/books/peggy-cooper-cafritzs-collection-of-african-american-art-rises-from-the-ashes/2018/02/15/b9e85f5c-0daa-11e8-8b0d-891602206fb7_story.html|title=Review {{!}} Peggy Cooper Cafritz\u2019s collection of African American art rises from the ashes|last=Valentine|first=Victoria L.|date=2018-02-15|work=Washington Post|access-date=2018-02-19|issn=0190-8286|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180217212528/https://www.washingtonpost.com/entertainment/books/peggy-cooper-cafritzs-collection-of-african-american-art-rises-from-the-ashes/2018/02/15/b9e85f5c-0daa-11e8-8b0d-891602206fb7_story.html|archivedate=2018-02-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://georgetowner.com/articles/2017/09/29/dave-chappelle-gives-emmy-ellington-school-gets-key-city/|title=Dave Chappelle Gives Emmy to Ellington School, Gets Key to Washington, D.C.|date=2017-09-29 |last=Devaney |first=Robert |work=The Georgetowner|access-date=2018-02-19|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180219081328/https://georgetowner.com/articles/2017/09/29/dave-chappelle-gives-emmy-ellington-school-gets-key-city/|archivedate=2018-02-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://georgetowner.com/articles/2017/11/09/articles20171109made-history-cox-graae-spack-designs-future/|title=Made by History: Cox Graae + Spack Designs for the Future |date=2017-11-09 |last=Selden |first=Richard |work=The Georgetowner|access-date=2018-02-19|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180219081328/https://georgetowner.com/articles/2017/11/09/articles20171109made-history-cox-graae-spack-designs-future/|archivedate=2018-02-19}}</ref>\n\nCafritz was DC school board president from 2000 to 2006.<ref name=\"USA\" /> She also served on the DC Commission on the Arts and Humanities and member of the board for many arts institutions.{{citation needed|date=February 2018}}\n\nIn addition to her philanthropic career, Cafritz was programming executive and documentary producer for WTOP-TV, an assistant at [[Post-Newsweek Stations]], to [[Harry Belafonte]] and [[M. Carl Holman]], president of the National Urban Coalition.<ref name=\"Bernstein 2018\" /> Cafritz was the first collector for many visual artists and has sponsored many projects including [[Spike Lee]]'s ''[[Malcolm X (1992 film)|Malcolm X]]''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://ew.com/movies/2017/11/18/malcolm-x-anniversary-spike-lee-bill-cosby-prince-oprah/|title=Spike Lee thanks Bill Cosby, Prince, Oprah on 25th anniversary of 'Malcolm X'|work=EW.com |date=2017-11-18 |last=Romano |first=Nick |access-date=2018-02-19|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171229222422/http://ew.com/movies/2017/11/18/malcolm-x-anniversary-spike-lee-bill-cosby-prince-oprah/|archivedate=2017-12-29|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009 a house fire destroyed her home in DC's [[Kent, Washington, D.C.|Kent neighborhood]], ravaging the eight-bedroom architectural landmark where she held salons and kept her art collection, one of the largest private collections of African American and African art.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/07/30/AR2009073004226.html|title=Fire at Home of Peggy Cooper Cafritz Scorches Washington's Cultural Landscape |last2=Brown |first2=DeNeen L. |last1=Montgomery |first1=David |date=2009-07-31|access-date=2018-02-19|issn=0190-8286|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171222041307/http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/07/30/AR2009073004226.html|archivedate=2017-12-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite magazine|url=http://www.oprah.com/home/home-decorating-inside-the-home-of-art-patron-peggy-cooper-cafritz/all|title=Art House: Supporting Talented Young Artists of Color|work=Oprah.com |last=Medwick |first=Cathleen |date=August 2009 |access-date=2018-02-19}}</ref> Among those 300 works destroyed in the fire were works by [[Jacob Lawrence]] and [[Romare Bearden]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ellingtonschool.org/arts/|title=Duke Ellington School of the Arts|website=Duke Ellington School of the Arts|access-date=2018-02-19|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170628003819/http://www.ellingtonschool.org/arts/|archivedate=2017-06-28}}</ref> She reached a settlement with the [[District of Columbia Water and Sewer Authority]] over the fire for their inadequate pressure in the hydrants.<ref name=nyt.obit>{{cite news |last=Green |first=Penelope |date=23 February 2018 |title=Peggy Cooper Cafritz, Patron of Black Artists, Dies at 7 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/02/23/obituaries/peggy-cooper-cafritz-patron-of-black-artists-dies-at-70.html |work=NY Times |location=New York |access-date=23 February 2018}}</ref>\n\nCafritz moved to [[Dupont Circle]] in 2001 and continued to grow her collection.<ref name=\"Fox\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fox5dc.com/news/local-news/dc-visionary-peggy-cooper-cafritz-co-founder-of-duke-ellington-school-dies-at-age-70|publisher=[[WTTG]]|title=DC visionary Peggy Cooper Cafritz, co-founder of Duke Ellington School dies at age 70|accessdate=February 18, 2018|date=February 18, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180219081327/http://www.fox5dc.com/news/local-news/dc-visionary-peggy-cooper-cafritz-co-founder-of-duke-ellington-school-dies-at-age-70|archivedate=February 19, 2018}}</ref> Included in the Cafritz collection is [[Carrie Mae Weems]], [[El Anatsui]], [[Chris Ofili]], [[Mickalene Thomas]], [[Glenn Ligon]], [[Simone Leigh]], [[Titus Kaphar]], [[LaToya Ruby Frazier]], [[William Villalongo]], [[Tschabalala Self]], [[Nathaniel Mary Quinn]] and [[Njideka Akunyili Crosby]], whose work is featured on the cover of a 2018 book about Cafritz's collection.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.amazon.com/Fired-Up-Ready-Demanding-Collections/dp/0847860582/ref=sr_1_1?ie=UTF8&qid=1519006204&sr=8-1&keywords=peggy+cooper+cafritz|title=Fired Up! Ready to Go!: Finding Beauty, Demanding Equity: An African American Life in Art. The Collections of Peggy Cooper Cafritz|last=Cafritz|first=Peggy Cooper|last2=Golden|first2=Thelma|last3=Marshall|first3=Kerry James|last4=Leigh|first4=Simone|last5=McMillan|first5=Uri|date=2018-02-20|publisher=Rizzoli Electa|isbn=9780847860586|location=New York}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/magazine/six-years-after-the-fire-peggy-cooper-cafritz-has-a-new-home-and-collection/2015/09/22/22558aa2-518c-11e5-933e-7d06c647a395_story.html|title=Six years after the fire, Peggy Cooper Cafritz has a new home and collection|last=Davis|first=Marcia|date=2015-09-24|work=Washington Post|access-date=2018-02-19|issn=0190-8286|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180218024806/https://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/magazine/six-years-after-the-fire-peggy-cooper-cafritz-has-a-new-home-and-collection/2015/09/22/22558aa2-518c-11e5-933e-7d06c647a395_story.html|archivedate=2018-02-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.culturetype.com/2018/02/15/art-agency-new-book-by-peggy-cooper-cafritz-explores-her-collections-and-undying-support-for-artists/|title=Art & Agency: New Book by Peggy Cooper Cafritz Explores Her Collections and Undying Support for Artists |date=2018-02-15 |last=Valentine |first=Victoria L. |website=www.culturetype.com|access-date=2018-02-19|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180219081327/http://www.culturetype.com/2018/02/15/art-agency-new-book-by-peggy-cooper-cafritz-explores-her-collections-and-undying-support-for-artists/|archivedate=2018-02-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://dc.curbed.com/2017/7/20/16003824/art-home-dupont-circle-peggy-cooper-cafritz|title=See arts patron Peggy Cooper Cafritz\u2019s massive collection in this $5.5M Dupont Circle condo\u2019s photos|work=Curbed DC |date=2017-07-20 |last=Goldchain |first=Michelle |access-date=2018-02-19|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170926013018/https://dc.curbed.com/2017/7/20/16003824/art-home-dupont-circle-peggy-cooper-cafritz|archivedate=2017-09-26}}</ref><ref name=NYTimes-2015>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/01/15/garden/peggy-cooper-cafritz-everything-in-a-big-way.html|title=Peggy Cooper Cafritz: Everything in a Big Way|last=Green|first=Penelope|date=2015-01-14|work=The New York Times|access-date=2018-02-19|issn=0362-4331|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160128174843/http://www.nytimes.com/2015/01/15/garden/peggy-cooper-cafritz-everything-in-a-big-way.html|archivedate=2016-01-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wmagazine.com/story/6-rising-artists-to-watch-2018|title=The 6 Rising Artists You Must Know In 2018|last=Solway|first=Diane|work=W Magazine |date=2017-12-04 |access-date=2018-02-19|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171205015253/https://www.wmagazine.com/story/6-rising-artists-to-watch-2018|archivedate=2017-12-05}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nIn 1981, Cafritz married multimillionaire real estate executive Conrad Cafritz, son of the real estate developer and philanthropist [[Morris Cafritz]].<ref>https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/lifestyle/magazine/1990/02/25/cafritz-v-cafritz/9f486a14-9672-4802-802e-0e470a9f1507/</ref> She was Catholic and he was Jewish.<ref name= aisfor/> Together they had three children.<ref name=\"Bernstein 2018\" /> The couple divorced in 1998; in the divorce documents, Peggy said her husband had cheated on her and had contempt for her friends and family who were black.<ref name=NYTimes-2015/><ref name= aisfor/> Cafritz had many mentees, unofficial foster children, and several godchildren, including [[Susan Rice]] and her brother, John.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Green|first=Penelope|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/01/15/garden/peggy-cooper-cafritz-everything-in-a-big-way.html|title=Peggy Cooper Cafritz: Everything in a Big Way|date=2015-01-14|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-03-09|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nCafritz died in Washington, D.C. on February 18, 2018, from complications from pneumonia after a period of declining health.<ref name=\"Bernstein 2018\" /> She bequeathed more than 250 works by Black artists to the [[Duke Ellington School of the Arts]] and over 400 to the [[Studio Museum in Harlem]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Acquisitions of the month: October 2018 |url=https://www.apollo-magazine.com/acquisitions-of-the-month-october-2018/ |website=Apollo Magazine}}</ref> marking the largest gift ever made of contemporary art by artists of African descent.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://studiomuseum.org/press-release/peggy-cooper-cafritz-bequeaths-over-400-works-studio-museum|title=Peggy Cooper Cafritz Bequeaths Over 400 Works to the Studio Museum|date=2018-10-10|website=The Studio Museum in Harlem|language=en|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref> \n\n== Works and publications ==\n* {{cite book|last1=Cafritz|first1=Peggy Cooper|title=Fired Up! Ready to Go! Finding Beauty, Demanding Equity. The African American Art Collections of Peggy Cooper Cafritz|date=2018|publisher=Rizzoli International Publications|location=New York|isbn=978-0-847-86058-6|oclc=1021038973}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.ellingtonschool.org/about/history-mission/ Duke Ellington School of the Arts Project]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cooper Cafritz, Peggy}}\n[[Category:1947 births]]\n[[Category:2018 deaths]]\n[[Category:American art collectors]]\n[[Category:American women philanthropists]]\n[[Category:Activist Women's Voices oral history project]]\n[[Category:Women collectors]]\n[[Category:Women art collectors]]\n[[Category:People from Mobile, Alabama]]\n[[Category:Philanthropists from Alabama]]\n[[Category:Philanthropists from Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Members of the District of Columbia Board of Education]]\n[[Category:Saint Mary's College (Indiana) alumni]]\n[[Category:Deaths from pneumonia]]\n[[Category:Infectious disease deaths in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:African-American Catholics]]\n[[Category:Art educators]]\n[[Category:George Washington University Law School alumni]]\n[[Category:Catholics from Alabama]]\n[[Category:People from Dupont Circle]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name = Peggy Cooper Cafritz\n| image = \n| alt = \n| caption = \n| birth_name = Pearl Alice Cooper\n| birth_date = {{birth date|1947|4|07|mf=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Mobile, Alabama]], U.S.\n| death_date = {{Death date and age|2018|02|18|1947|04|07}}\n| death_place = [[Washington, D.C.]], U.S.\n| other_names = Peggy Cooper\n| occupation = [[Art collector]], educator, [[civil rights activist]], [[philanthropy|philanthropist]]\n| alma_mater = [[Saint Mary's College (Indiana)|St Mary's College]],<br/>[[George Washington University]]\n| years_active = 1960s\u20132018\n| spouse = {{marriage|Conrad Cafritz|1981|1998}}\n| children = 3 \n}}\n'''Peggy Cooper Cafritz''' (born '''Pearl Alice Cooper'''; April 7, 1947 \u2013 February 18, 2018) was an American [[art collector]], educator, [[civil rights activist]], [[Philanthropy|philanthropist]] and socialite.<ref name=\"Bernstein 2018\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/obituaries/peggy-coopercafritz-grande-dame-of-the-washington-arts-and-education-scene-dies-at-70/2018/02/18/0f6bb948-14c1-11e8-92c9-376b4fe57ff7_story.html|title=Peggy Cooper Cafritz, grande dame of the Washington arts and education scene, dies at 70|last=Bernstein|first=Adam|date=2018-02-18|work=Washington Post|access-date=2018-02-18|issn=0190-8286|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180218185553/https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/obituaries/peggy-coopercafritz-grande-dame-of-the-washington-arts-and-education-scene-dies-at-70/2018/02/18/0f6bb948-14c1-11e8-92c9-376b4fe57ff7_story.html|archivedate=2018-02-18}}</ref><ref name=\"Rosen\">{{cite news |last1=Rosen |first1=Miss |title=The art world remembers the force of nature who we lost too soon |url=http://www.dazeddigital.com/art-photography/article/39708/1/art-world-remembers-peggy-cooper-cafritz-the-force-of-nature-who-lost-too-soon |accessdate=6 April 2019 |work=Dazed |date=18 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nBorn Pearl Alice Cooper, Peggy Cafritz belonged to one of the wealthiest African American families in [[Mobile, Alabama]]. Her childhood nickname \"Peggy\" was eventually legally changed to be her real name. The Cooper family gained their wealth through Peggy's father who worked for the family business of insurance and mortuary services. Her parents were socially acquainted with famous jazz musician [[Duke Ellington]], namesake of the [[Duke Ellington School of the Arts]] which Cafritz would go on to co-found.<ref name= aisfor>Blum, Justin (May 21, 2002). \"A Is for Activist: D.C. Schools President Peggy Cooper Cafritz Raises Her Hand\". ''The Washington Post''. p. C1.</ref>\n\nAs a child, Cooper attended a segregated Catholic elementary school for black children and was raised Catholic.<ref name=\"USA\" /> The racism she experienced would shape her world view. \n\nThe summer after graduating from high school, Cafritz and her friends tried to be served at a [[drive-in restaurant]]; the [[Civil Rights Act of 1964]] had recently been passed, forbidding racial discrimination in restaurants. When Cafritz and her friends buzzed for service, several white teenage boys approached their car, spat on them, threw soda through their car window, and jumped on the hood of the car. Two police officers watched from nearby but did nothing.<ref name= aisfor/>\n\nIn 1964, during the [[civil rights movement]], Cafritz graduated from [[Saint Mary's College (Indiana)|St Mary's College]] in Indiana and moved to [[Washington, D.C.]] to attend [[George Washington University]] where she organized the [[Black Students Union|Black Student Union]] and worked on the integration of fraternities and sororities in 1968.<ref name=\"USA\"/> She received her law degree from George Washington University in 1971.<ref name=\"USA\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/2018/02/18/activist-peggy-cooper-cafritz-who-helped-build-model-public-education-dies-70/349617002/|title=Activist Peggy Cooper Cafritz, who helped build a model for public education, dies at 70|work=USA TODAY|access-date=2018-02-19|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180219081327/https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/2018/02/18/activist-peggy-cooper-cafritz-who-helped-build-model-public-education-dies-70/349617002/|archivedate=2018-02-19}}</ref> In the 1970s she was the youngest fellow of [[Woodrow Wilson International Center for Scholars]].<ref name=\"Bernstein 2018\" />\n\n==Career==\nCafritz wanted to bring the money of the white people and the power of the black people in Washington, D.C., together in unity.<ref name=\"Bernstein 2018\" />\n\nIn 1968, Cafritz she bused in inner-city students to attend a black arts festival that the organized.<ref name=\"Bernstein 2018\"/> Afterwards she and choreographer [[Mike Malone (choreographer)|Mike Malone]] created a summer arts workshop for at-risk high school children. This program became the magnet school [[Duke Ellington School of the Arts]], which she and Malone founded in 1974 and which they modeled after New York City's [[High School of Performing Arts]].<ref name=\"Bernstein 2018\"/> Their goal was to start an arts-education program for local children who had showed promise but had no outlet to demonstrate their potential.<ref name= aisfor/> Ellington was the only public high school in Washington, D.C., to train students with a curriculum in both academics and intensive professional arts training.{{citation needed|date=February 2018}} Ellington alumni include [[Dave Chappelle]], [[Denyce Graves]], [[Hank Willis Thomas]] and [[Meshell Ndegeocello]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/10/04/arts/design/hank-willis-thomas-art.html|title=Artist Sews Together Sports and Geopolitics|last=Vecsey|first=George|date=2017-10-04|work=The New York Times|access-date=2018-02-19|issn=0362-4331|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171004095704/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/10/04/arts/design/hank-willis-thomas-art.html|archivedate=2017-10-04}}</ref><ref name=\"Valentine 2018\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/entertainment/books/peggy-cooper-cafritzs-collection-of-african-american-art-rises-from-the-ashes/2018/02/15/b9e85f5c-0daa-11e8-8b0d-891602206fb7_story.html|title=Review {{!}} Peggy Cooper Cafritz\u2019s collection of African American art rises from the ashes|last=Valentine|first=Victoria L.|date=2018-02-15|work=Washington Post|access-date=2018-02-19|issn=0190-8286|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180217212528/https://www.washingtonpost.com/entertainment/books/peggy-cooper-cafritzs-collection-of-african-american-art-rises-from-the-ashes/2018/02/15/b9e85f5c-0daa-11e8-8b0d-891602206fb7_story.html|archivedate=2018-02-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://georgetowner.com/articles/2017/09/29/dave-chappelle-gives-emmy-ellington-school-gets-key-city/|title=Dave Chappelle Gives Emmy to Ellington School, Gets Key to Washington, D.C.|date=2017-09-29 |last=Devaney |first=Robert |work=The Georgetowner|access-date=2018-02-19|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180219081328/https://georgetowner.com/articles/2017/09/29/dave-chappelle-gives-emmy-ellington-school-gets-key-city/|archivedate=2018-02-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://georgetowner.com/articles/2017/11/09/articles20171109made-history-cox-graae-spack-designs-future/|title=Made by History: Cox Graae + Spack Designs for the Future |date=2017-11-09 |last=Selden |first=Richard |work=The Georgetowner|access-date=2018-02-19|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180219081328/https://georgetowner.com/articles/2017/11/09/articles20171109made-history-cox-graae-spack-designs-future/|archivedate=2018-02-19}}</ref>\n\nCafritz was DC school board president from 2000 to 2006.<ref name=\"USA\" /> She also served on the DC Commission on the Arts and Humanities and member of the board for many arts institutions.{{citation needed|date=February 2018}}\n\nIn addition to her philanthropic career, Cafritz was programming executive and documentary producer for WTOP-TV, an assistant at [[Post-Newsweek Stations]], to [[Harry Belafonte]] and [[M. Carl Holman]], president of the National Urban Coalition.<ref name=\"Bernstein 2018\" /> Cafritz was the first collector for many visual artists and has sponsored many projects including [[Spike Lee]]'s ''[[Malcolm X (1992 film)|Malcolm X]]''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://ew.com/movies/2017/11/18/malcolm-x-anniversary-spike-lee-bill-cosby-prince-oprah/|title=Spike Lee thanks Bill Cosby, Prince, Oprah on 25th anniversary of 'Malcolm X'|work=EW.com |date=2017-11-18 |last=Romano |first=Nick |access-date=2018-02-19|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171229222422/http://ew.com/movies/2017/11/18/malcolm-x-anniversary-spike-lee-bill-cosby-prince-oprah/|archivedate=2017-12-29|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009 a house fire destroyed her home in DC's [[Kent, Washington, D.C.|Kent neighborhood]], ravaging the eight-bedroom architectural landmark where she held salons and kept her art collection, one of the largest private collections of African American and African art.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/07/30/AR2009073004226.html|title=Fire at Home of Peggy Cooper Cafritz Scorches Washington's Cultural Landscape |last2=Brown |first2=DeNeen L. |last1=Montgomery |first1=David |date=2009-07-31|access-date=2018-02-19|issn=0190-8286|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171222041307/http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/07/30/AR2009073004226.html|archivedate=2017-12-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite magazine|url=http://www.oprah.com/home/home-decorating-inside-the-home-of-art-patron-peggy-cooper-cafritz/all|title=Art House: Supporting Talented Young Artists of Color|work=Oprah.com |last=Medwick |first=Cathleen |date=August 2009 |access-date=2018-02-19}}</ref> Among those 300 works destroyed in the fire were works by [[Jacob Lawrence]] and [[Romare Bearden]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ellingtonschool.org/arts/|title=Duke Ellington School of the Arts|website=Duke Ellington School of the Arts|access-date=2018-02-19|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170628003819/http://www.ellingtonschool.org/arts/|archivedate=2017-06-28}}</ref> She reached a settlement with the [[District of Columbia Water and Sewer Authority]] over the fire for their inadequate pressure in the hydrants.<ref name=nyt.obit>{{cite news |last=Green |first=Penelope |date=23 February 2018 |title=Peggy Cooper Cafritz, Patron of Black Artists, Dies at 7 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/02/23/obituaries/peggy-cooper-cafritz-patron-of-black-artists-dies-at-70.html |work=NY Times |location=New York |access-date=23 February 2018}}</ref>\n\nCafritz moved to [[Dupont Circle]] in 2001 and continued to grow her collection.<ref name=\"Fox\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fox5dc.com/news/local-news/dc-visionary-peggy-cooper-cafritz-co-founder-of-duke-ellington-school-dies-at-age-70|publisher=[[WTTG]]|title=DC visionary Peggy Cooper Cafritz, co-founder of Duke Ellington School dies at age 70|accessdate=February 18, 2018|date=February 18, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180219081327/http://www.fox5dc.com/news/local-news/dc-visionary-peggy-cooper-cafritz-co-founder-of-duke-ellington-school-dies-at-age-70|archivedate=February 19, 2018}}</ref> Included in the Cafritz collection is [[Carrie Mae Weems]], [[El Anatsui]], [[Chris Ofili]], [[Mickalene Thomas]], [[Glenn Ligon]], [[Simone Leigh]], [[Titus Kaphar]], [[LaToya Ruby Frazier]], [[William Villalongo]], [[Tschabalala Self]], [[Nathaniel Mary Quinn]] and [[Njideka Akunyili Crosby]], whose work is featured on the cover of a 2018 book about Cafritz's collection.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.amazon.com/Fired-Up-Ready-Demanding-Collections/dp/0847860582/ref=sr_1_1?ie=UTF8&qid=1519006204&sr=8-1&keywords=peggy+cooper+cafritz|title=Fired Up! Ready to Go!: Finding Beauty, Demanding Equity: An African American Life in Art. The Collections of Peggy Cooper Cafritz|last=Cafritz|first=Peggy Cooper|last2=Golden|first2=Thelma|last3=Marshall|first3=Kerry James|last4=Leigh|first4=Simone|last5=McMillan|first5=Uri|date=2018-02-20|publisher=Rizzoli Electa|isbn=9780847860586|location=New York}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/magazine/six-years-after-the-fire-peggy-cooper-cafritz-has-a-new-home-and-collection/2015/09/22/22558aa2-518c-11e5-933e-7d06c647a395_story.html|title=Six years after the fire, Peggy Cooper Cafritz has a new home and collection|last=Davis|first=Marcia|date=2015-09-24|work=Washington Post|access-date=2018-02-19|issn=0190-8286|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180218024806/https://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/magazine/six-years-after-the-fire-peggy-cooper-cafritz-has-a-new-home-and-collection/2015/09/22/22558aa2-518c-11e5-933e-7d06c647a395_story.html|archivedate=2018-02-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.culturetype.com/2018/02/15/art-agency-new-book-by-peggy-cooper-cafritz-explores-her-collections-and-undying-support-for-artists/|title=Art & Agency: New Book by Peggy Cooper Cafritz Explores Her Collections and Undying Support for Artists |date=2018-02-15 |last=Valentine |first=Victoria L. |website=www.culturetype.com|access-date=2018-02-19|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180219081327/http://www.culturetype.com/2018/02/15/art-agency-new-book-by-peggy-cooper-cafritz-explores-her-collections-and-undying-support-for-artists/|archivedate=2018-02-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://dc.curbed.com/2017/7/20/16003824/art-home-dupont-circle-peggy-cooper-cafritz|title=See arts patron Peggy Cooper Cafritz\u2019s massive collection in this $5.5M Dupont Circle condo\u2019s photos|work=Curbed DC |date=2017-07-20 |last=Goldchain |first=Michelle |access-date=2018-02-19|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170926013018/https://dc.curbed.com/2017/7/20/16003824/art-home-dupont-circle-peggy-cooper-cafritz|archivedate=2017-09-26}}</ref><ref name=NYTimes-2015>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/01/15/garden/peggy-cooper-cafritz-everything-in-a-big-way.html|title=Peggy Cooper Cafritz: Everything in a Big Way|last=Green|first=Penelope|date=2015-01-14|work=The New York Times|access-date=2018-02-19|issn=0362-4331|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160128174843/http://www.nytimes.com/2015/01/15/garden/peggy-cooper-cafritz-everything-in-a-big-way.html|archivedate=2016-01-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wmagazine.com/story/6-rising-artists-to-watch-2018|title=The 6 Rising Artists You Must Know In 2018|last=Solway|first=Diane|work=W Magazine |date=2017-12-04 |access-date=2018-02-19|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171205015253/https://www.wmagazine.com/story/6-rising-artists-to-watch-2018|archivedate=2017-12-05}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nIn 1981, Cafritz married multimillionaire real estate executive Conrad Cafritz, son of the real estate developer and philanthropist [[Morris Cafritz]].<ref>https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/lifestyle/magazine/1990/02/25/cafritz-v-cafritz/9f486a14-9672-4802-802e-0e470a9f1507/</ref> She was Catholic and he was Jewish.<ref name= aisfor/> Together they had three children.<ref name=\"Bernstein 2018\" /> The couple divorced in 1998; in the divorce documents, Peggy said her husband had cheated on her and had contempt for her friends and family who were black.<ref name=NYTimes-2015/><ref name= aisfor/> Cafritz had many mentees, unofficial foster children, and several godchildren, including [[Susan Rice]] and her brother, John.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Green|first=Penelope|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/01/15/garden/peggy-cooper-cafritz-everything-in-a-big-way.html|title=Peggy Cooper Cafritz: Everything in a Big Way|date=2015-01-14|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-03-09|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nCafritz died in Washington, D.C. on February 18, 2018, from complications from pneumonia after a period of declining health.<ref name=\"Bernstein 2018\" /> She bequeathed more than 650 works by Black artists to the [[Duke Ellington School of the Arts]] and the [[Studio Museum in Harlem]]. <ref>{{cite web |title=Acquisitions of the month: October 2018 |url=https://www.apollo-magazine.com/acquisitions-of-the-month-october-2018/ |website=Apollo Magazine}}</ref>\n\n== Works and publications ==\n* {{cite book|last1=Cafritz|first1=Peggy Cooper|title=Fired Up! Ready to Go! Finding Beauty, Demanding Equity. The African American Art Collections of Peggy Cooper Cafritz|date=2018|publisher=Rizzoli International Publications|location=New York|isbn=978-0-847-86058-6|oclc=1021038973}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.ellingtonschool.org/about/history-mission/ Duke Ellington School of the Arts Project]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cooper Cafritz, Peggy}}\n[[Category:1947 births]]\n[[Category:2018 deaths]]\n[[Category:American art collectors]]\n[[Category:American women philanthropists]]\n[[Category:Activist Women's Voices oral history project]]\n[[Category:Women collectors]]\n[[Category:Women art collectors]]\n[[Category:People from Mobile, Alabama]]\n[[Category:Philanthropists from Alabama]]\n[[Category:Philanthropists from Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Members of the District of Columbia Board of Education]]\n[[Category:Saint Mary's College (Indiana) alumni]]\n[[Category:Deaths from pneumonia]]\n[[Category:Infectious disease deaths in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:African-American Catholics]]\n