{"title_page": "Jeffrey Shapiro", "text_new": "{{Infobox scientist\n|name              = Jeffrey H. Shapiro\n|image             = Jeffrey Shapiro at MIT.png\n|caption           = \n|birth_date        = \n|birth_place       = \n|death_date        = \n|death_place       = \n|residence         = [[United States]]\n|citizenship       = \n|nationality       = American\n|ethnicity         = \n|fields            = [[Physicist]]\n|workplaces        = [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]], \n[[Case Western Reserve University]]\n|alma_mater        = [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]]\n|doctoral_advisor  = [[Robert S. Kennedy]]\n|academic_advisors = \n|doctoral_students = \n|notable_students  = \n|known_for         = [[quantum communication]], [[squeezed state]], [[ghost imaging]]\n|author_abbrev_bot = \n|author_abbrev_zoo = \n|influences        = \n|influenced        = \n|awards            = \n|religion          =\n|signature         =  <!--(filename only)-->\n|footnotes         = \n}}\n'''Jeffrey H. Shapiro''' is the [[Julius A. Stratton]] Professor of [[Electrical Engineering and Computer Science]] at the [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]] and the former director of the [[Research Laboratory of Electronics at MIT|Research Laboratory of Electronics]].<ref>[http://www.rle.mit.edu/shapiro Jeffrey Shapiro]</ref> He made seminal contributions to understanding the fundamental quantum limits on [[communications]], generation, detection, and application of quantum [[squeezed state]], [[ghost imaging]], and [[quantum information science]].  He invented the microchannel-plate spatial light modulator with [[Cardinal Warde]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Kalb|first=Gilbert|title=Massively Parallel, Optical, and Neural Computing in the United States|year=1992|publisher=IOS Press|page=91|url=https://books.google.com/?id=7Ao4TBf4uv4C&pg=PA91 |author2=Robert Moxley|isbn=9789051990973}}</ref>\n\n== Biography ==\nShapiro received the S.B., S.M., E.E., and Ph.D. degrees in electrical engineering from MIT in 1967, 1968, 1969, and 1970, respectively. From 1970 to 1973, he was on the faculty of [[Case Western Reserve University]]. From 1973 to 1985, he was an associate professor of electrical engineering at MIT, and in 1985, he was promoted to professor of electrical engineering. He became the Julius A. Stratton Professor in 1999.\n\nFrom 1989 to 1999, Shapiro served as the associate department head of MIT's department of electrical engineering and computer science. He was appointed director of the Research Laboratory of Electronics in 2001.<ref>[http://www.rle.mit.edu/rle-professor-jeffrey-h-shapiro-julius-a-stratton-professor-of-electrical-engineering-named-the-seventh-director-of-the-research-laboratory-of-electronics/ Shapiro appointed the seventh Director of RLE]</ref> He is also a director of MIT's Optical and Quantum Communications Group.<ref>{{cite web|last=Hardesty|first=Larry|title=Making quantum encryption practical|url=http://phys.org/news/2013-05-quantum-encryption.html|work=Phys.org|accessdate=20 November 2013|date=May 21, 2013}}</ref>\n\n== Research ==\nShapiro's research focuses on utilizing [[quantum mechanics|quantum mechanical effects]] to develop [[quantum metrology|metrology]] tools and applications whose performance greatly exceeds what can be realized with conventional, [[classical physics|classical-physics]] systems. In particular, his group investigated the quantum limits on [[optical communications]] and derived the [[quantum capacity|capacity]] of quantum channels. His group also demonstrated high-performance [[quantum entanglement|entanglement]] sources and took advantage of these sources to implement [[quantum key distribution]] systems. Shapiro's group pioneered in developing [[quantum illumination]],<ref>Zheshen Zhang, Maria Tengner, Tian Zhong, Franco N.C. Wong, and Jeffrey H. Shapiro, ''Entanglement's benefit survives an entanglement-breaking channel'', [[Phys. Rev. Lett.]] '''111''', 010501 (2013) ([http://link.aps.org/doi/10.1103/PhysRevLett.111.010501])</ref> which enables use of entanglement in lossy and noisy environments.<ref>''Quantum Communications: Broken quantum links still work'', [[Nature (journal)|Nature]] '''499''', 129 (2013) ([http://www.nature.com/nature/journal/v499/n7457/full/499129a.html])</ref><ref>''Fragility of entanglement no bar to quantum secrets'', [[New Scientist]] July 17, 2013([https://www.newscientist.com/article/dn23882-fragility-of-entanglement-no-bar-to-quantum-secrets.html#.Uo15S5GzweY])</ref>\n\n== Honors ==\n* Fellow of the [[Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers]] (IEEE)\n* Fellow of the [[Optical Society of America]] (OSA)\n* Fellow of the [[American Physical Society]] (APS)\n* Fellow of the [[Institute of Physics]] (IoP)\n* Fellow of [[SPIE]]\n* 2008 International Quantum Communication Award<ref>[http://qcmc2012.org/awards/ Laureates of the Quantum Communication Award]</ref>\n* 2008 IEEE/LEOS Quantum Electronics Award<ref>{{cite web|title=2008 IEEE/LEOS Quantum Electronics Award Recipients: Jeffrey H. Shapiro and Horace P. Yuen|url=http://photonicssociety.org/newsletters/jun08/quantum_recipients.html|work=IEEE website|accessdate=20 November 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130709144737/http://photonicssociety.org/newsletters/jun08/quantum_recipients.html|archive-date=9 July 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.rle.mit.edu/shapiro Jeffrey Shapiro's Home Page at MIT]\n*[http://www.rle.mit.edu/qoptics Optical and Quantum Communications Group at MIT]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Shapiro, Jeffrey}}\n[[Category:Massachusetts Institute of Technology faculty]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox scientist\n|name              = Jeffrey H. Shapiro\n|image             = Jeffrey Shapiro at MIT.png\n|caption           = \n|birth_date        = \n|birth_place       = \n|death_date        = \n|death_place       = \n|residence         = [[United States]]\n|citizenship       = \n|nationality       = American\n|ethnicity         = \n|fields            = [[Physicist]]\n|workplaces        = [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]], \n[[Case Western Reserve University]]\n|alma_mater        = [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]]\n|doctoral_advisor  = [[Robert S. Kennedy]]\n|academic_advisors = \n|doctoral_students = \n|notable_students  = \n|known_for         = [[quantum communication]], [[squeezed state]], [[ghost imaging]]\n|author_abbrev_bot = \n|author_abbrev_zoo = \n|influences        = \n|influenced        = \n|awards            = \n|religion          =\n|signature         =  <!--(filename only)-->\n|footnotes         = \n}}\n'''Jeffrey H. Shapiro''' is the [[Julius A. Stratton]] Professor of [[Electrical Engineering and Computer Science]] at the [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]] and the former Director of the [[Research Laboratory of Electronics at MIT|Research Laboratory of Electronics]].<ref>[http://www.rle.mit.edu/shapiro Jeffrey Shapiro]</ref> He made seminal contributions to understanding the fundamental quantum limits on [[communications]], generation, detection, and application of quantum [[squeezed state]], [[ghost imaging]], and [[quantum information science]].  He invented the microchannel-plate spatial light modulator with [[Cardinal Warde]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Kalb|first=Gilbert|title=Massively Parallel, Optical, and Neural Computing in the United States|year=1992|publisher=IOS Press|page=91|url=https://books.google.com/?id=7Ao4TBf4uv4C&pg=PA91 |author2=Robert Moxley|isbn=9789051990973}}</ref>\n\n== Biography ==\nShapiro received the S.B., S.M., E.E., and Ph.D. degrees in Electrical Engineering from MIT in 1967, 1968, 1969, and 1970, respectively. From 1970 to 1973, he was on the faculty of [[Case Western Reserve University]]. From 1973 to 1985, he was an Associate Professor of Electrical Engineering at MIT, and in 1985, he was promoted to Professor of Electrical Engineering. He became the Julius A. Stratton Professor in 1999.\n\nFrom 1989 to 1999, Shapiro served as the Associate Department Head of MIT's Department of Electrical Engineering and Computer Science. He was appointed Director of the Research Laboratory of Electronics in 2001.<ref>[http://www.rle.mit.edu/rle-professor-jeffrey-h-shapiro-julius-a-stratton-professor-of-electrical-engineering-named-the-seventh-director-of-the-research-laboratory-of-electronics/ Shapiro appointed the seventh Director of RLE]</ref> He is also a director of MIT's Optical and Quantum Communications Group.<ref>{{cite web|last=Hardesty|first=Larry|title=Making quantum encryption practical|url=http://phys.org/news/2013-05-quantum-encryption.html|work=Phys.org|accessdate=20 November 2013|date=May 21, 2013}}</ref>\n\n== Research ==\nShapiro's research focuses on utilizing [[quantum mechanics|quantum mechanical effects]] to develop [[quantum metrology|metrology]] tools and applications whose performance greatly exceeds what can be realized with conventional, [[classical physics|classical-physics]] systems. In particular, his group investigated the quantum limits on [[optical communications]] and derived the [[quantum capacity|capacity]] of quantum channels. His group also demonstrated high-performance [[quantum entanglement|entanglement]] sources and took advantage of these sources to implement [[quantum key distribution]] systems. Shapiro's group pioneered in developing [[quantum illumination]],<ref>Zheshen Zhang, Maria Tengner, Tian Zhong, Franco N.C. Wong, and Jeffrey H. Shapiro, ''Entanglement's benefit survives an entanglement-breaking channel'', [[Phys. Rev. Lett.]] '''111''', 010501 (2013) ([http://link.aps.org/doi/10.1103/PhysRevLett.111.010501])</ref> which enables use of entanglement in lossy and noisy environments.<ref>''Quantum Communications: Broken quantum links still work'', [[Nature (journal)|Nature]] '''499''', 129 (2013) ([http://www.nature.com/nature/journal/v499/n7457/full/499129a.html])</ref><ref>''Fragility of entanglement no bar to quantum secrets'', [[New Scientist]] July 17, 2013([https://www.newscientist.com/article/dn23882-fragility-of-entanglement-no-bar-to-quantum-secrets.html#.Uo15S5GzweY])</ref>\n\n== Honors ==\n* Fellow of the [[Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers]] (IEEE)\n* Fellow of the [[Optical Society of America]] (OSA)\n* Fellow of the [[American Physical Society]] (APS)\n* Fellow of the [[Institute of Physics]] (IoP)\n* Fellow of [[SPIE]]\n* 2008 International Quantum Communication Award<ref>[http://qcmc2012.org/awards/ Laureates of the Quantum Communication Award]</ref>\n* 2008 IEEE/LEOS Quantum Electronics Award<ref>{{cite web|title=2008 IEEE/LEOS Quantum Electronics Award Recipients: Jeffrey H. Shapiro and Horace P. Yuen|url=http://photonicssociety.org/newsletters/jun08/quantum_recipients.html|work=IEEE website|accessdate=20 November 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130709144737/http://photonicssociety.org/newsletters/jun08/quantum_recipients.html|archive-date=9 July 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.rle.mit.edu/shapiro Jeffrey Shapiro's Home Page at MIT]\n*[http://www.rle.mit.edu/qoptics Optical and Quantum Communications Group at MIT]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Shapiro, Jeffrey}}\n[[Category:Massachusetts Institute of Technology faculty]]\n", "name_user": "Chris the speller", "label": "safe", "comment": "replaced: Director \u2192 director, Associate Professor \u2192 associate professor, Director \u2192 director, Electrical Engineering \u2192 electrical engineering (2), Department of Electrical Engineering \u2192 department of electrical engineering, etc.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jeffrey_Shapiro"}
{"title_page": "Pioneer Square South and Pioneer Square North stations", "text_new": "{{About-distinguish2|the light rail stations in Portland, Oregon|[[Pioneer Square station]] in Seattle}}\n{{Infobox Station\n | name          = {{MAX infobox header|Pioneer Square South|blue|red}}{{MAX infobox header|Pioneer Square North|blue|red}}\n | type          = [[MAX Light Rail]] stations\n | image         = Pioneer Square South MAX station.jpg\n | image_caption = The platform of Pioneer Square South station in 2009\n | address       = [[Pioneer Courthouse Square]]<br/>[[Portland, Oregon|Portland]], [[Oregon]], U.S.\n | country       =\n | line          = {{TMTC bullet|blue|size=5}}{{nbsp}}[[MAX Blue Line|Blue Line]]{{br}}{{TMTC bullet|red|size=5}}{{nbsp}}[[MAX Red Line|Red Line]]\n | coordinates   = {{Coord|45|31|08|N|122|40|46|W|format=dms|display=inline,title|type:landmark_region:US-OR}}\n | connections   ={{rint|bus|1}}{{nbsp}}'''[[Portland Transit Mall]]'''{{br}}{{rint|tram|1}}{{nbsp}}'''[[MAX Light Rail]]''':{{Block indent|em=1|1=<nowiki />{{TMTC bullet|green|size=5}}{{nbsp}}[[MAX Green Line|Green Line]]{{br}}{{TMTC bullet|orange|size=5}}{{nbsp}}[[MAX Orange Line|Orange Line]]{{br}}{{TMTC bullet|yellow|size=5}}{{nbsp}}[[MAX Yellow Line|Yellow Line]]{{br}}at [[Pioneer Courthouse/Southwest 6th and Pioneer Place/Southwest 5th stations|Pioneer Courthouse/Southwest 6th and Pioneer Place/Southwest 5th]]}}\n | platform      = 2 one-way [[side platform]]s\n | tracks        = 1 per split\n | parking       = \n | bicycle       = \n | baggage_check =\n | passengers    = 1,796 (Pioneer Square South){{br}}3,327 (Pioneer Square North){{br}}5,123 (total){{br}}weekday boardings (fall 2019)<ref name=\"pax-census-fall-2019\">{{cite web |url=https://trimet.org/about/pdf/census/2019fall/max_station_passenger_census_report.pdf |title=TriMet MAX Light Rail Passenger Census \u2013 Fall 2019 |publisher=TriMet |access-date=March 10, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200310153349/https://trimet.org/about/pdf/census/2019fall/max_station_passenger_census_report.pdf |archive-date=March 10, 2020}}</ref>\n | pass_year     =\n | pass_percent  =\n | pass_system   =\n | opened        = {{Start date|1986|09|05}}\n | closed        = \n | rebuilt       = \n | ADA           = yes\n | code          = \n | owned         = [[TriMet]]\n | services      ={{s-rail|title=TMTC}}\n{{s-text|text='''North'''}}\n{{s-line|system=TMTC|line=Blue|previous=Galleria/SW 10th Ave|next=Morrison/SW 3rd|rows2=2|oneway2=yes}}\n{{s-line|system=TMTC|line=Red|previous=Galleria/SW 10th Ave|hide2=yes}}\n{{s-text|text='''South'''}}\n{{s-line|system=TMTC|line=Blue|previous=Library/SW 9th Ave|next=Yamhill District|rows1=2|oneway1=yes}}\n{{s-line|system=TMTC|line=Red|next=Yamhill District|hide1=yes}}\n | other_services_collapsible=yes\n | other_services_header=Former services\n | other_services=\n{{s-rail|title=TMTC}}\n{{s-text|text='''North'''}}\n{{s-line|system=TMTC|line=Blue|previous=Galleria/SW 10th Ave|next=Mall/SW 5th Ave|rows2=3|oneway2=yes|notemid=''1986\u20132020''|note2=(''closed'')}}\n{{s-line|system=TMTC|line=Red|previous=Galleria/SW 10th Ave|hide2=yes|notemid=''2004\u20132009''}}\n{{s-line|system=TMTC|line=Yellow|previous=Galleria/SW 10th Ave|oneway2=yes|notemid=''2004\u20132009''|hide2=yes|type=2009}}\n{{s-text|text='''South'''}}\n{{s-line|system=TMTC|line=Blue|previous=Library/SW 9th Ave|next=Mall/SW 4th Ave|rows1=3|oneway1=yes|notemid=''1986\u20132020''|note2=(''closed'')}}\n{{s-line|system=TMTC|line=Red|next=Mall/SW 4th Ave|hide1=yes|notemid=''2001\u20132020''|note2=(''closed'')}}\n{{s-line|system=TMTC|line=Yellow|previous=Library/SW 9th Ave|next=Mall/SW 4th Ave|notemid=''2004\u20132009''|hide1=yes|oneway1=true|note2=(''closed'')}}\n | mpassengers   =\n}}\n'''Pioneer Square South''' and '''Pioneer Square North''' are a pair of [[light rail]] stations in [[Portland, Oregon]], United States, served by [[TriMet]] as part of its [[MAX Light Rail]] system. The platforms occupy the sidewalks of Southwest Yamhill and Morrison streets between Broadway and 6th Avenue in [[downtown Portland]], and are the 21st and 7th stops eastbound on the [[MAX Blue Line|Blue Line]] and the [[MAX Red Line|Red Line]], respectively. They are situated directly west of the [[Portland Transit Mall]] at [[Pioneer Courthouse Square]]; these stations, along with the [[Pioneer Courthouse/Southwest 6th and Pioneer Place/Southwest 5th stations]] that are served by the [[MAX Green Line|Green]], [[MAX Orange Line|Orange]], and [[MAX Yellow Line|Yellow]] lines, mark the only [[Interchange station|transfer point]] in the MAX system where riders can board any of the five existing lines.\n\nThe Pioneer Square stations are among the 27 original stations built as part of the Banfield light rail project\u2014Portland's first light rail line. They opened along with the inaugural service of MAX on September 5, 1986. The Red Line began serving the stations in September 2001, initially connecting downtown to [[Portland International Airport]]. In 2003, the Red Line extended westward to [[Beaverton, Oregon|Beaverton]]. The Yellow Line also served the stations from 2004 to 2009, connecting downtown to the [[Portland Metropolitan Exposition Center|Expo Center]]; TriMet rerouted this line to serve the transit mall in August 2009.\n\n==History==\n{{See also|Pioneer Courthouse Square}}\n\nThe Portland city block bound by Southwest Morrison and Yamhill streets to the north and south, and 6th Avenue and Broadway to the east and west had previously been occupied by various structures, including a school, a hotel, and a parking garage. In March 1856, a proclamation created School District No. 1, which built the city's first permanent public school at this location.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://oregonhistoryproject.org/articles/historical-records/central-school/#.XnI3dKhKhhE |title=Central School |publisher=[[Oregon Historical Society]] |date=March 17, 2018 |access-date=March 18, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150930101129/https://www.oregonhistoryproject.org/articles/historical-records/central-school/ |archive-date=March 18, 2020}}</ref> Referred to as Central School, it opened on May 7, 1858.<ref>{{cite news |last=Killen |first=John |title=Throwback Thursday: Portland public schools, started in 1850s, took awhile to catch on |newspaper=[[The Oregonian]] |date=June 11, 2015 |url=https://www.oregonlive.com/history/2015/06/throwback_thursday_portland_pu.html |access-date=March 18, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318151006/https://www.oregonlive.com/history/2015/06/throwback_thursday_portland_pu.html |archive-date=March 18, 2020}}</ref> With the arrival of the [[Northern Pacific Railway]] to Portland in 1883, [[Henry Villard]] purchased the site of Central School for $75,000 and began building a first class hotel. The ensuing [[Panic of 1884]] halted construction for five years due to the collapse of Villard's finances. Construction resumed with the help of George B. Markle and other local investors, and the [[Portland Hotel]] opened on April 7, 1890. Over the next several decades, the Portland Hotel would establish itself as the city's social center and the \"place to see and be seen.\"<ref name=\"portland-hotel\">{{cite news |author=<!--no by line; staff writer(s)--> |title=The Portland Hotel: Once the place to see and be seen |date=April 2, 2011 |newspaper=The Oregonian |url=https://www.oregonlive.com/O/2011/04/the_portland_hotel_once_the_pl.html |access-date=March 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Pioneer Square MAX station north - Portland, Oregon.JPG|thumb|left|The westbound platform on the north side of the square, 2011]]\n\n[[Meier & Frank]] purchased the Portland Hotel in 1944 and continued operating it until 1951, after which the company tore it down and built a parking garage in its place.<ref name=\"portland-hotel\"/><ref name=\"history-pioneer-photos\">{{cite news |url=https://www.oregonlive.com/multimedia/2013/10/the_history_of_pioneer_courtho.html |last=Vattiat |first=Drew |title=The history of Pioneer Courthouse Square in photos |date=October 4, 2013 |newspaper=The Oregonian |access-date=April 16, 2020}}</ref> In January 1969, Meier & Frank request a permit for the construction of an 11-story, 800-car parking garage, which the [[Government of Portland, Oregon|Portland City Council]] and the Portland Planning Commission rejected following a series of heated public hearings.<ref name=\"began\">{{cite book |last=Halprin |first=Lawrence |last2=Halprin |first2=Anna |title=Where the revolution began |editor=Gragg, Randy |publisher=Spacemaker Press |location=Washington, DC |year=2009 |isbn=978-0-9824392-1-0 |oclc= 449857189}}</ref> The controversial proposal led the local business community and the city to pursue a comprehensive downtown plan that envisioned turning the site into a public space instead.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://thesquarepdx.org/history/ |title=History: Timeline |publisher=Pioneer Courthouse Square Administrative Office |access-date=April 16, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.oregonlive.com/multimedia/2013/10/history_of_pioneer_courthouse.html |last=Vattiat |first=Drew |title=History of Pioneer Courthouse Square: The winning design and four rejected finalists from 1980 (photos) |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=October 4, 2013 |access-date=April 16, 2020}}</ref> After several negotiations between then-Mayor [[Neil Goldschmidt]] and Meier & Frank, the city purchased the property and in 1980, announced a national design competition for a plaza that would be called [[Pioneer Courthouse Square]].<ref name=\"history-pioneer-photos\"/>\n\nPortland's first light rail line, which planners referred to as the Banfield light rail project, received federal approval for construction in September 1980. Over a year later, TriMet published a conceptual design report of the project for the city that outlined a 27-station, {{convert|15.1|mi|km|1|adj=on}} line, including a pair of light rail stations at Pioneer Courthouse Square. The platforms would be situated along the north and south ends of the square on Southwest Morrison and Yamhill streets.<ref name=\"Conceptual Design\">{{cite report |author=Tri-County Metropolitan Transportation District of Oregon |title=Banfield Light Rail Project: Conceptual Design Information for the City of Portland |url=https://pdxscholar.library.pdx.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1008&context=oscdl_trimet |publisher=TriMet Collection |volume=9 |date=November 1, 1981 |access-date=July 27, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150928184313/http://pdxscholar.library.pdx.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1008&context=oscdl_trimet |archivedate=September 28, 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref>{{rp|37\u201338}} Construction of the line commenced in April 1983 in Gresham and largely progressed from east to west,<ref>{{cite news |last=Federman |first=Stan |title=Tri-Met opens bids on first light-rail track work |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=March 11, 1983 |page=B1}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Federman |first=Stan |title=Light-rail work gets go-ahead |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=March 31, 1983 |page=D16}}</ref> with the downtown segment among the final sections to be completed.<ref name=\"light-rails-jolly\">{{cite news |last=Federman |first=Stan |title=Light rail's jolly trolley progress on track |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=March 4, 1986 |page=B5}}</ref> Street and sidewalk reconstruction work finally reached downtown in March 1984.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--no by line; staff writer(s)--> |title=Light-rail work [photo and caption only] |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=March 10, 1984 |quote=Ralph L. Mowatt, a welder for Portland General Electric Co., cuts iron beam in street at Southwest First Avenue and Morrison Street on Friday as construction on the Banfield light-rail project moved downtown this week with utilities beginning to relocate lines. |page=C1}}</ref> While work continued on the line, the city finished building the square and dedicated it on April 6.<ref>{{cite news |last=Ritz |first=Richard E. |title=Flow of people will complete square's design |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=April 3, 1984 |page=B5}}</ref><ref name=\"soul\">{{cite news |last=Gragg |first=Randy |title=Pioneer Courthouse Square: Soul of the City\" (10th anniversary feature) |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=April 4, 1994 |pages=A1, A6}}</ref> By March 1986, major light rail construction work had ceased.<ref name=\"light-rails-jolly\"/> Line testing in downtown began with the arrival of the first light rail car the following May.<ref>{{cite news |last=Murphy |first=Bill |title=Downtown debut |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=May 9, 1986 |page=1 |quote=The first Tri-Met light-rail car to appear downtown is towed up Southwest Morrison Street Thursday. It will be open for public inspection at downtown locations for the next week.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=<!--no by line; staff writer(s)--> |title=Shoppers get first look at Tri-Met light-rail car |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=May 9, 1986 |page=D8}}</ref> \n\nOn September 5, 1986, TriMet officially opened the light rail line, which it named Metropolitan Area Express (MAX), to the public.<ref>{{cite news |last=Federman |first=Stan |title=All aboard! MAX on track; ride free |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=September 5, 1986 |page=1}}</ref> A three-day celebration took place across the route, including at Pioneer Courthouse Square, which hosted an opening ceremony and several concerts.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--no by line; staff writer(s)--> |title=Riding the Rails; Schedule of events: Sept. 5\u20137 |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=September 5, 1986 |page=T4}}</ref> More than 3,000 people gathered at the square to welcome the 11:45 am arrival of the first train from Gresham.<ref>{{cite news |last=Hayakawa |first=Alan R. |title=Whistle-stop tour inaugurates MAX light rail |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=September 6, 1986 |page=B6}}</ref> Between 1986 and 1998, only one MAX service that ran from [[Cleveland Avenue station|Cleveland Avenue]] in central Gresham to [[Library/Southwest 9th Avenue and Galleria/Southwest 10th Avenue stations|11th Avenue]] served the Pioneer Square stations. In 1998, TriMet extended this service farther west to [[Hatfield Government Center station|Hatfield Government Center]] in downtown Hillsboro with the opening of the Westside MAX. On September 10, 2001, the Red Line, which connected downtown\u2014and eventually [[Beaverton Transit Center|Beaverton]]\u2014to [[Portland International Airport station|Portland International Airport]] became the second line to serve the station.<ref name=\"oreg-2001-city-that-moves\">{{cite news|last1=Oliver|first1=Gordon|title=Portland now 'the city that moves', mayor says [opening of MAX Red Line]|newspaper=The Oregonian|date=September 11, 2001|page=1}}</ref><ref name=\"direct service Beaverton\">{{cite news |last=Leeson |first=Fred |date=August 27, 2003 |title=MAX fares increase, direct service from Beaverton to PDX starts |newspaper=The Oregonian |page=D2}}</ref> From 2004 to 2009, the Yellow Line, which ran to the [[Expo Center station|Expo Center]] in North Portland, also stopped at this station until TriMet rerouted it to the new light rail tracks on Portland Transit Mall in August 2009.<ref name=\"tribune2009-0828\">{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=New MAX line opens downtown |newspaper=[[Portland Tribune]] |date=August 28, 2009 |url=http://pamplinmedia.com/component/content/article?id=54413 |access-date=May 13, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150103091415/http://pamplinmedia.com/component/content/article?id=54413 |archive-date=January 3, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Station details==\n{{stack|float=right|[[File:Pioneer Courthouse Square - west half.jpg|thumb|Entrance to the visitor information center, which also houses TriMet's ticket office]]}}\n{|table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=3\n|-\n|style=\"border-top:solid 1px gray;border-bottom:solid 1px gray;\" width=70 rowspan=3 valign=top|'''Sidewalk{{br}}platform'''\n|style=\"border-top:solid 1px gray;\" width=100 rowspan=2 valign=top| '''Westbound'''\n|style=\"border-top:solid 1px gray;\" width=530| \u2190 {{TMTC bullet|blue|size=5}} '''[[MAX Blue Line|Blue Line]]''' towards {{stn|Hatfield Government Center}} <small>([[Library/Southwest 9th Avenue and Galleria/Southwest 10th Avenue stations|Galleria/Southwest 10th Avenue]])</small>\n|-\n| \u2190 {{TMTC bullet|red|size=5}} '''[[MAX Red Line|Red Line]]''' towards [[Beaverton Transit Center]] <small>(Galleria/Southwest 10th Avenue)</small>\n|-\n|style=\"border-top:solid 2px black;border-right:solid 2px black;border-left:solid 2px black;border-bottom:solid 1px gray;text-align:center;\" colspan=2|<small>[[Side platform]], doors will open on the left</small>\n|-\n|colspan=3 align=center| [[Pioneer Courthouse Square]]\n|-\n|style=\"border-top:solid 1px gray;border-bottom:solid 1px gray;\" rowspan=3 valign=top|'''Sidewalk{{br}}platform'''\n|style=\"border-top:solid 1px black;border-right:solid 2px black;border-left:solid 2px black;border-bottom:solid 2px black;text-align:center;\" colspan=2|{{small|Side platform, doors will open on the left}}\n|-\n|style=\"border-bottom:solid 1px gray;\" rowspan=2 valign=top| '''Eastbound'''\n| <span style=\"color:white\">\u2192</span> {{TMTC bullet|blue|size=5}} '''Blue Line''' towards {{stn|Cleveland Avenue}} <small>([[Yamhill District and Morrison/Southwest 3rd Avenue stations|Yamhill District]])</small> \u2192\n|-\n|style=\"border-bottom:solid 1px gray;\"| <span style=\"color:white\">\u2192</span> {{TMTC bullet|red|size=5}} '''Red Line''' towards {{stn|Portland International Airport}} <small>(Yamhill District)</small> \u2192\n|}\n\nThe Pioneer Square stations occupy the sidewalks facing Southwest Yamhill and Morrison streets between Broadway and 6th Avenue in downtown Portland. Pioneer Courthouse Square, commonly known as \"Portland's Living Room\", is situated between the stations' platforms.<ref name=\"community-building-2007\">{{cite web |url=https://trimet.org/pdfs/publications/community_sourcebook.pdf |title=Community Building Sourcebook: Land use and transportation initiatives in Portland, Oregon |date=December 2007 |publisher=TriMet |access-date=April 18, 2020}}</ref>{{rp|6\u20136}} Amenities include garbage cans, shelters, and schedule information displays. TriMet's ticket office is located inside the visitor information center on the west side of the square.<ref name=\"community-building-2007\"/>{{rp|6\u20136}} Oregon's first [[Starbucks]] outlet sits adjacent to the western edge of the westbound platform.<ref>{{cite news|title=Starbucks grabs spot in Portland coffee trade|newspaper=The Oregonian|date=August 23, 1989|last=Hamburg|first=Ken}}</ref>\n\nTriMet considers the square a [[transit hub]].<ref name=\"community-building-2007\"/>{{rp|6\u20136}} It is the only location in the MAX system where all five existing light rail services interconnect.<ref name=\"Transit Mall map\">{{cite map |url=https://trimet.org/maps/pdf/citycenter.pdf |title=Portland City Center and Transit Mall |publisher=TriMet |access-date=July 30, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190210193921/https://trimet.org/maps/pdf/citycenter.pdf |archive-date=February 10, 2019}}</ref> The northbound light rail tracks on the Portland Transit Mall run along the immediate east side of the platforms on 6th Avenue; this provides a direct transfer to the MAX platform of [[Pioneer Courthouse/Southwest 6th and Pioneer Place/Southwest 5th stations|Pioneer Courthouse/Southwest 6th station]] across the street,<ref>{{google maps |url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/Pioneer+Courthouse%2FSW+6th+Ave+MAX+Stn/@45.5185392,-122.6779511,18.25z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x54950a0501406169:0xdba87b6b880304d2!8m2!3d45.5189148!4d-122.678597 |title=Pioneer Courthouse/SW 6th Ave MAX Stn |access-date=March 10, 2020}}</ref> which is served by the [[MAX Green Line|Green]] and Yellow lines.<ref name=\"Transit Mall map\"/> On the opposite end of this adjacent block, which is occupied by the [[Pioneer Courthouse]],<ref>{{google maps |url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/Pioneer+Courthouse/@45.5185392,-122.6779511,18.25z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x54950a05062e150d:0x8802daba8b93f854!8m2!3d45.5186849!4d-122.6785527 |title=Pioneer Courthouse |access-date=March 10, 2020}}</ref> is the southbound MAX station, Pioneer Place/Southwest 5th.<ref>{{google maps |url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/Pioneer+Place%2FSW+5th+Ave+MAX+Station/@45.5185392,-122.6779511,18.25z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x54950a050cf4ea0f:0x4cdf598044a8ad23!8m2!3d45.5183125!4d-122.6779392 |title=Pioneer Place/SW 5th Ave MAX Station |access-date=March 10, 2020}}</ref> This station is served by the Green and [[MAX Orange Line|Orange]] lines. The Pioneer Square stations also facilitate transfers to buses serving the Portland Transit Mall.<ref name=\"Transit Mall map\"/>\n\n===Service===\n\nThe Pioneer Square stations are served by the MAX Blue Line, which connects the stations to Beaverton and Hillsboro to the west and Gresham to the east, and the MAX Red Line, which connects the stations to Beaverton to the west and Portland International Airport to the east.<ref name=\"MAX system map\">{{cite map |url=https://trimet.org/maps/pdf/railsystem.pdf |title=Rail System Map with transfers |publisher=TriMet |access-date=July 25, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190210194620/https://trimet.org/maps/pdf/railsystem.pdf |archive-date=February 10, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://trimet.org/ride/stop.html?stop_id=8334 |title=Stop ID 8334 \u2013 Pioneer Square South MAX Station |publisher=TriMet |access-date=March 18, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://trimet.org/ride/stop.html?stop_id=8383 |title=Stop ID 8383 \u2013 Pioneer Square North MAX Station |publisher=TriMet |access-date=March 18, 2020}}</ref> The stations together recorded an average 5,123 riders on weekdays in fall 2019.<ref name=\"pax-census-fall-2019\"/> From the stations, westbound trains take approximately 25{{nbsp}}minutes to reach Beaverton Transit Center and 50{{nbsp}}minutes to reach Hatfield Government Center station.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://trimet.org/schedules/w/t1100_1.pdf |title=MAX Blue Line, Weekday Westbound to Portland City Center and Hillsboro |publisher=TriMet |access-date=May 23, 2019}}</ref> Eastbound trains take approximately 35{{nbsp}}minutes to reach Portland International Airport station and 50{{nbs}}minutes to reach Cleveland Avenue station.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://trimet.org/schedules/w/t1100_0.pdf |title=MAX Blue Line, Weekday Eastbound to Portland City Center and Gresham |publisher=TriMet |access-date=May 23, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{{{cite web |url=https://trimet.org/schedules/w/t1090_0.pdf |title=MAX Red Line, Weekday To Portland City Center and Airport |publisher=TriMet |access-date=May 23, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* {{cite web |url=https://trimet.org/ride/stop.html?stop_id=8334 |title=Stop ID 8334 \u2013 Pioneer Square South MAX Station |publisher=TriMet}}\n* {{cite web |url=https://trimet.org/ride/stop.html?stop_id=8383 |title=Stop ID 8383 \u2013 Pioneer Square North MAX Station |publisher=TriMet}}\n\n{{TriMet railway stations|Blue=y|Red=y}}\n\n[[Category:1986 establishments in Oregon]]\n[[Category:MAX Blue Line]]\n[[Category:MAX Light Rail double stations]]\n[[Category:MAX Red Line]]\n[[Category:Railway stations in Portland, Oregon]]\n[[Category:Railway stations in the United States opened in 1986]]\n[[Category:Southwest Portland, Oregon]]\n", "text_old": "{{About-distinguish2|the light rail stations in Portland, Oregon|[[Pioneer Square station]] in Seattle}}\n{{Infobox Station\n | name          = {{MAX infobox header|Pioneer Square South|blue|red}}{{MAX infobox header|Pioneer Square North|blue|red}}\n | type          = [[MAX Light Rail]] stations\n | image         = Pioneer Square South MAX station.jpg\n | image_caption = The platform of Pioneer Square South station in 2009\n | address       = [[Pioneer Courthouse Square]]<br/>[[Portland, Oregon|Portland]], [[Oregon]], U.S.\n | country       =\n | line          = {{TMTC bullet|blue|size=5}}{{nbsp}}[[MAX Blue Line|Blue Line]]{{br}}{{TMTC bullet|red|size=5}}{{nbsp}}[[MAX Red Line|Red Line]]\n | coordinates   = {{Coord|45|31|08|N|122|40|46|W|format=dms|display=inline,title|type:landmark_region:US-OR}}\n | connections   ={{rint|bus|1}}{{nbsp}}'''[[Portland Transit Mall]]'''{{br}}{{rint|tram|1}}{{nbsp}}'''[[MAX Light Rail]]''':{{Block indent|em=1|1=<nowiki />{{TMTC bullet|green|size=5}}{{nbsp}}[[MAX Green Line|Green Line]]{{br}}{{TMTC bullet|orange|size=5}}{{nbsp}}[[MAX Orange Line|Orange Line]]{{br}}{{TMTC bullet|yellow|size=5}}{{nbsp}}[[MAX Yellow Line|Yellow Line]]{{br}}at [[Pioneer Courthouse/Southwest 6th and Pioneer Place/Southwest 5th stations|Pioneer Courthouse/Southwest 6th and Pioneer Place/Southwest 5th]]}}\n | platform      = 2 one-way [[side platform]]s\n | tracks        = 1 per split\n | parking       = \n | bicycle       = \n | baggage_check =\n | passengers    = 1,796 (Pioneer Square South){{br}}3,327 (Pioneer Square North){{br}}5,123 (total){{br}}weekday boardings (fall 2019)<ref name=\"pax-census-fall-2019\">{{cite web |url=https://trimet.org/about/pdf/census/2019fall/max_station_passenger_census_report.pdf |title=TriMet MAX Light Rail Passenger Census \u2013 Fall 2019 |publisher=TriMet |access-date=March 10, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200310153349/https://trimet.org/about/pdf/census/2019fall/max_station_passenger_census_report.pdf |archive-date=March 10, 2020}}</ref>\n | pass_year     =\n | pass_percent  =\n | pass_system   =\n | opened        = {{Start date|1986|09|05}}\n | closed        = \n | rebuilt       = \n | ADA           = yes\n | code          = \n | owned         = [[TriMet]]\n | services      ={{s-rail|title=TMTC}}\n{{s-text|text='''North'''}}\n{{s-line|system=TMTC|line=Blue|previous=Galleria/SW 10th Ave|next=Morrison/SW 3rd|rows2=2|oneway2=yes}}\n{{s-line|system=TMTC|line=Red|previous=Galleria/SW 10th Ave|hide2=yes}}\n{{s-text|text='''South'''}}\n{{s-line|system=TMTC|line=Blue|previous=Library/SW 9th Ave|next=Yamhill District|rows1=2|oneway1=yes}}\n{{s-line|system=TMTC|line=Red|next=Yamhill District|hide1=yes}}\n | other_services_collapsible=yes\n | other_services_header=Former services\n | other_services=\n{{s-rail|title=TMTC}}\n{{s-text|text='''North'''}}\n{{s-line|system=TMTC|line=Blue|previous=Galleria/SW 10th Ave|next=Mall/SW 5th Ave|rows2=3|oneway2=yes|notemid=''1986\u20132020''|note2=(''closed'')}}\n{{s-line|system=TMTC|line=Red|previous=Galleria/SW 10th Ave|hide2=yes|notemid=''2004\u20132009''}}\n{{s-line|system=TMTC|line=Yellow|previous=Galleria/SW 10th Ave|oneway2=yes|notemid=''2004\u20132009''|hide2=yes|type=2009}}\n{{s-text|text='''South'''}}\n{{s-line|system=TMTC|line=Blue|previous=Library/SW 9th Ave|next=Mall/SW 4th Ave|rows1=3|oneway1=yes|notemid=''1986\u20132020''|note2=(''closed'')}}\n{{s-line|system=TMTC|line=Red|next=Mall/SW 4th Ave|hide1=yes|notemid=''2001\u20132020''|note2=(''closed'')}}\n{{s-line|system=TMTC|line=Yellow|previous=Library/SW 9th Ave|next=Mall/SW 4th Ave|notemid=''2004\u20132009''|hide1=yes|oneway1=true|note2=(''closed'')}}\n | mpassengers   =\n}}\n'''Pioneer Square South''' and '''Pioneer Square North''' are a pair of [[light rail]] stations in [[Portland, Oregon]], United States, served by [[TriMet]] as part of its [[MAX Light Rail]] system. The platforms occupy the sidewalks of Southwest Yamhill and Morrison streets between Broadway and 6th Avenue in [[downtown Portland]], and are the 21st and 7th stops eastbound on the [[MAX Blue Line|Blue Line]] and the [[MAX Red Line|Red Line]], respectively. They are situated directly west of the [[Portland Transit Mall]] at [[Pioneer Courthouse Square]]; these stations, along with the [[Pioneer Courthouse/Southwest 6th and Pioneer Place/Southwest 5th stations]] that are served by the [[MAX Green Line|Green]], [[MAX Orange Line|Orange]], and [[MAX Yellow Line|Yellow]] lines, mark the only [[Interchange station|transfer point]] in the MAX system where riders can board any of the five existing lines.\n\nThe Pioneer Square stations are among the 27 original stations built as part of the Banfield light rail project\u2014Portland's first light rail line. They opened along with the inaugural service of MAX on September 5, 1986. The Red Line began serving the stations in September 2001, initially connecting downtown to [[Portland International Airport]]. In 2003, the Red Line extended westward to [[Beaverton, Oregon|Beaverton]]. The Yellow Line also served the stations from 2004 to 2009, connecting downtown to the [[Portland Metropolitan Exposition Center|Expo Center]]; TriMet rerouted this line to serve the transit mall in August 2009.\n\n==History==\n{{See also|Pioneer Courthouse Square}}\n\nThe Portland city block bound by Southwest Morrison and Yamhill streets to the north and south, and 6th Avenue and Broadway to the east and west had previously been occupied by various structures, including a school, a hotel, and a parking garage. In March 1856, a proclamation created School District No. 1, which built the city's first permanent public school at this location.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://oregonhistoryproject.org/articles/historical-records/central-school/#.XnI3dKhKhhE |title=Central School |publisher=[[Oregon Historical Society]] |date=March 17, 2018 |access-date=March 18, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150930101129/https://www.oregonhistoryproject.org/articles/historical-records/central-school/ |archive-date=March 18, 2020}}</ref> Referred to as Central School, it opened on May 7, 1858.<ref>{{cite news |last=Killen |first=John |title=Throwback Thursday: Portland public schools, started in 1850s, took awhile to catch on |newspaper=[[The Oregonian]] |date=June 11, 2015 |url=https://www.oregonlive.com/history/2015/06/throwback_thursday_portland_pu.html |access-date=March 18, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318151006/https://www.oregonlive.com/history/2015/06/throwback_thursday_portland_pu.html |archive-date=March 18, 2020}}</ref> With the arrival of the [[Northern Pacific Railway]] to Portland in 1883, [[Henry Villard]] purchased the site of Central School for $75,000 and began building a first class hotel. The ensuing [[Panic of 1884]] halted construction for five years due to the collapse of Villard's finances. Construction resumed with the help of George B. Markle and other local investors, and the [[Portland Hotel]] opened on April 7, 1890. Over the next several decades, the Portland Hotel would establish itself as the city's social center and the \"place to see and be seen.\"<ref name=\"portland-hotel\">{{cite news |author=<!--no by line; staff writer(s)--> |title=The Portland Hotel: Once the place to see and be seen |date=April 2, 2011 |newspaper=The Oregonian |url=https://www.oregonlive.com/O/2011/04/the_portland_hotel_once_the_pl.html |access-date=March 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Pioneer Square MAX station north - Portland, Oregon.JPG|thumb|left|The westbound platform on the north side of the square, 2011]]\n\n[[Meier & Frank]] purchased the Portland Hotel in 1944 and continued operating it until 1951, after which the company tore it down and built a parking garage in its place.<ref name=\"portland-hotel\"/><ref name=\"history-pioneer-photos\">{{cite news |url=https://www.oregonlive.com/multimedia/2013/10/the_history_of_pioneer_courtho.html |last=Vattiat |first=Drew |title=The history of Pioneer Courthouse Square in photos |date=October 4, 2013 |newspaper=The Oregonian |access-date=April 16, 2020}}</ref> In January 1969, Meier & Frank request a permit for the construction of an 11-story, 800-car parking garage, which the [[Government of Portland, Oregon|Portland City Council]] and the Portland Planning Commission rejected following a series of heated public hearings.<ref name=\"began\">{{cite book |last=Halprin |first=Lawrence |last2=Halprin |first2=Anna |title=Where the revolution began |editor=Gragg, Randy |publisher=Spacemaker Press |location=Washington, DC |year=2009 |isbn=978-0-9824392-1-0 |oclc= 449857189}}</ref> The controversial proposal led the local business community and the city to pursue a comprehensive downtown plan that envisioned turning the site into a public space instead.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://thesquarepdx.org/history/ |title=History: Timeline |publisher=Pioneer Courthouse Square Administrative Office |access-date=April 16, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.oregonlive.com/multimedia/2013/10/history_of_pioneer_courthouse.html |last=Vattiat |first=Drew |title=History of Pioneer Courthouse Square: The winning design and four rejected finalists from 1980 (photos) |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=October 4, 2013 |access-date=April 16, 2020}}</ref> After several negotiations between then-Mayor [[Neil Goldschmidt]] and Meier & Frank, the city purchased the property and in 1980, announced a national design competition for a plaza that would be called [[Pioneer Courthouse Square]].<ref name=\"history-pioneer-photos\"/>\n\nPortland's first light rail line, which planners referred to as the Banfield light rail project, received federal approval for construction in September 1980. Over a year later, TriMet published a conceptual design report of the project for the city that outlined a 27-station, {{convert|15.1|mi|km|1|adj=on}} line, including a pair of light rail stations at Pioneer Courthouse Square. The platforms would be situated along the north and south ends of the square on Southwest Morrison and Yamhill streets.<ref name=\"Conceptual Design\">{{cite report |author=Tri-County Metropolitan Transportation District of Oregon |title=Banfield Light Rail Project: Conceptual Design Information for the City of Portland |url=https://pdxscholar.library.pdx.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1008&context=oscdl_trimet |publisher=TriMet Collection |volume=9 |date=November 1, 1981 |access-date=July 27, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150928184313/http://pdxscholar.library.pdx.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1008&context=oscdl_trimet |archivedate=September 28, 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref>{{rp|37\u201338}} Construction of the line commenced in April 1983 in Gresham and largely progressed from east to west,<ref>{{cite news |last=Federman |first=Stan |title=Tri-Met opens bids on first light-rail track work |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=March 11, 1983 |page=B1}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Federman |first=Stan |title=Light-rail work gets go-ahead |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=March 31, 1983 |page=D16}}</ref> with the downtown segment among the final sections to be completed.<ref name=\"light-rails-jolly\">{{cite news |last=Federman |first=Stan |title=Light rail's jolly trolley progress on track |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=March 4, 1986 |page=B5}}</ref> Street and sidewalk reconstruction work finally reached downtown in March 1984.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--no by line; staff writer(s)--> |title=Light-rail work [photo and caption only] |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=March 10, 1984 |quote=Ralph L. Mowatt, a welder for Portland General Electric Co., cuts iron beam in street at Southwest First Avenue and Morrison Street on Friday as construction on the Banfield light-rail project moved downtown this week with utilities beginning to relocate lines. |page=C1}}</ref> While work continued on the line, the city finished building the square and dedicated it on April 6.<ref>{{cite news |last=Ritz |first=Richard E. |title=Flow of people will complete square's design |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=April 3, 1984 |page=B5}}</ref><ref name=\"soul\">{{cite news |last=Gragg |first=Randy |title=Pioneer Courthouse Square: Soul of the City\" (10th anniversary feature) |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=April 4, 1994 |pages=A1, A6}}</ref> By March 1986, major light rail construction work had ceased.<ref name=\"light-rails-jolly\"/> Line testing in downtown began with the arrival of the first light rail car the following May.<ref>{{cite news |last=Murphy |first=Bill |title=Downtown debut |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=May 9, 1986 |page=1 |quote=The first Tri-Met light-rail car to appear downtown is towed up Southwest Morrison Street Thursday. It will be open for public inspection at downtown locations for the next week.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=<!--no by line; staff writer(s)--> |title=Shoppers get first look at Tri-Met light-rail car |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=May 9, 1986 |page=D8}}</ref> \n\nOn September 5, 1986, TriMet officially opened the light rail line, which it named Metropolitan Area Express (MAX), to the public.<ref>{{cite news |last=Federman |first=Stan |title=All aboard! MAX on track; ride free |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=September 5, 1986 |page=1}}</ref> A three-day celebration took place across the route, including at Pioneer Courthouse Square, which hosted an opening ceremony and several concerts.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--no by line; staff writer(s)--> |title=Riding the Rails; Schedule of events: Sept. 5\u20137 |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=September 5, 1986 |page=T4}}</ref> More than 3,000 people gathered at the square to welcome the 11:45 am arrival of the first train from Gresham.<ref>{{cite news |last=Hayakawa |first=Alan R. |title=Whistle-stop tour inaugurates MAX light rail |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=September 6, 1986 |page=B6}}</ref> Between 1986 and 1998, only one MAX service that ran from [[Cleveland Avenue station|Cleveland Avenue]] in central Gresham to [[Library/Southwest 9th Avenue and Galleria/Southwest 10th Avenue stations|11th Avenue]] served the Pioneer Square stations. In 1998, TriMet extended this service farther west to [[Hatfield Government Center station|Hatfield Government Center]] in downtown Hillsboro with the opening of the Westside MAX. On September 10, 2001, the Red Line, which connected downtown\u2014and eventually [[Beaverton Transit Center|Beaverton]]\u2014to [[Portland International Airport station|Portland International Airport]] became the second line to serve the station.<ref name=\"oreg-2001-city-that-moves\">{{cite news|last1=Oliver|first1=Gordon|title=Portland now 'the city that moves', mayor says [opening of MAX Red Line]|newspaper=The Oregonian|date=September 11, 2001|page=1}}</ref><ref name=\"direct service Beaverton\">{{cite news |last=Leeson |first=Fred |date=August 27, 2003 |title=MAX fares increase, direct service from Beaverton to PDX starts |newspaper=The Oregonian |page=D2}}</ref> From 2004 to 2009, the Yellow Line, which ran to the [[Expo Center station|Expo Center]] in North Portland, also stopped at this station until TriMet rerouted it to the new light rail tracks on Portland Transit Mall in August 2009.<ref name=\"tribune2009-0828\">{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=New MAX line opens downtown |newspaper=[[Portland Tribune]] |date=August 28, 2009 |url=http://pamplinmedia.com/component/content/article?id=54413 |access-date=May 13, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150103091415/http://pamplinmedia.com/component/content/article?id=54413 |archive-date=January 3, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Station details==\n{{stack|float=right|[[File:Pioneer Courthouse Square - west half.jpg|thumb|Entrance to the visitor information center, which also houses TriMet's ticket office]]}}\n{|table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=3\n|-\n|style=\"border-top:solid 1px gray;border-bottom:solid 1px gray;\" width=70 rowspan=3 valign=top|'''Sidewalk{{br}}platform'''\n|style=\"border-top:solid 1px gray;\" width=100 rowspan=2 valign=top| '''Westbound'''\n|style=\"border-top:solid 1px gray;\" width=530| \u2190 {{TMTC bullet|blue|size=5}} '''[[MAX Blue Line|Blue Line]]''' towards {{stn|Hatfield Government Center}} <small>([[Library/Southwest 9th Avenue and Galleria/Southwest 10th Avenue stations|Galleria/Southwest 10th Avenue]])</small>\n|-\n| \u2190 {{TMTC bullet|red|size=5}} '''[[MAX Red Line|Red Line]]''' towards [[Beaverton Transit Center]] <small>(Galleria/Southwest 10th Avenue)</small>\n|-\n|style=\"border-top:solid 2px black;border-right:solid 2px black;border-left:solid 2px black;border-bottom:solid 1px gray;text-align:center;\" colspan=2|<small>[[Side platform]], doors will open on the left</small>\n|-\n|colspan=3 align=center| [[Pioneer Courthouse Square]]\n|-\n|style=\"border-top:solid 1px gray;border-bottom:solid 1px gray;\" rowspan=3 valign=top|'''Sidewalk{{br}}platform'''\n|style=\"border-top:solid 1px black;border-right:solid 2px black;border-left:solid 2px black;border-bottom:solid 2px black;text-align:center;\" colspan=2|{{small|Side platform, doors will open on the left}}\n|-\n|style=\"border-bottom:solid 1px gray;\" rowspan=2 valign=top| '''Eastbound'''\n| <span style=\"color:white\">\u2192</span> {{TMTC bullet|blue|size=5}} '''Blue Line''' towards {{stn|Cleveland Avenue}} <small>([[Yamhill District and Morrison/Southwest 3rd Avenue stations|Yamhill District]])</small> \u2192\n|-\n|style=\"border-bottom:solid 1px gray;\"| <span style=\"color:white\">\u2192</span> {{TMTC bullet|red|size=5}} '''Red Line''' towards {{stn|Portland International Airport}} <small>(Yamhill District)</small> \u2192\n|}\n\nThe Pioneer Square stations occupy the sidewalks facing Southwest Yamhill and Morrison streets between Broadway and 6th Avenue in downtown Portland. Pioneer Courthouse Square, commonly known as \"Portland's Living Room\", is situated between the stations' platforms.<ref name=\"community-building-2007\">{{cite web |url=https://trimet.org/pdfs/publications/community_sourcebook.pdf |title=Community Building Sourcebook: Land use and transportation initiatives in Portland, Oregon |date=December 2007 |publisher=TriMet |access-date=April 18, 2020}}</ref>{{rp|6\u20136}} Amenities include garbage cans, shelters, and schedule information displays. TriMet's ticket office is located inside the visitor information center on the west side of the square.<ref name=\"community-building-2007\"/>{{rp|6\u20136}} Oregon's first [[Starbucks]] outlet sits adjacent to the western edge of the westbound platform.<ref>{{cite news|title=Starbucks grabs spot in Portland coffee trade|newspaper=The Oregonian|date=August 23, 1989|last=Hamburg|first=Ken}}</ref>\n\nTriMet considers the square a [[transit hub]].<ref name=\"community-building-2007\"/>{{rp|6\u20136}} It is the only location in the MAX system where all five existing light rail services interconnect.<ref name=\"Transit Mall map\">{{cite map |url=https://trimet.org/maps/pdf/citycenter.pdf |title=Portland City Center and Transit Mall |publisher=TriMet |access-date=July 30, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190210193921/https://trimet.org/maps/pdf/citycenter.pdf |archive-date=February 10, 2019}}</ref> The northbound light rail tracks on the Portland Transit Mall run along the immediate east side of the platforms on 6th Avenue; this provides a direct transfer to the MAX platform of [[Pioneer Courthouse/Southwest 6th and Pioneer Place/Southwest 5th stations|Pioneer Courthouse/Southwest 6th station]] across the street,<ref>{{google maps |url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/Pioneer+Courthouse%2FSW+6th+Ave+MAX+Stn/@45.5185392,-122.6779511,18.25z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x54950a0501406169:0xdba87b6b880304d2!8m2!3d45.5189148!4d-122.678597 |title=Pioneer Courthouse/SW 6th Ave MAX Stn |access-date=March 10, 2020}}</ref> which is served by the [[MAX Green Line|Green]] and Yellow lines.<ref name=\"Transit Mall map\"/> On the opposite end of this adjacent block, which is occupied by the [[Pioneer Courthouse]],<ref>{{google maps |url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/Pioneer+Courthouse/@45.5185392,-122.6779511,18.25z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x54950a05062e150d:0x8802daba8b93f854!8m2!3d45.5186849!4d-122.6785527 |title=Pioneer Courthouse |access-date=March 10, 2020}}</ref> is the southbound MAX station, Pioneer Place/Southwest 5th.<ref>{{google maps |url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/Pioneer+Place%2FSW+5th+Ave+MAX+Station/@45.5185392,-122.6779511,18.25z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x54950a050cf4ea0f:0x4cdf598044a8ad23!8m2!3d45.5183125!4d-122.6779392 |title=Pioneer Place/SW 5th Ave MAX Station |access-date=March 10, 2020}}</ref> This station is served by the Green and [[MAX Orange Line|Orange]] lines. The Pioneer Square stations also facilitate transfers to buses serving the Portland Transit Mall.<ref name=\"Transit Mall map\"/>\n\n===Service===\n\nThe Pioneer Square stations are served by the MAX Blue Line, which connects the stations to Beaverton and Hillsboro to the west and Gresham to the east, and the MAX Red Line, which connects the stations to Beaverton to the west and Portland International Airport to the east.<ref name=\"MAX system map\">{{cite map |url=https://trimet.org/maps/pdf/railsystem.pdf |title=Rail System Map with transfers |publisher=TriMet |access-date=July 25, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190210194620/https://trimet.org/maps/pdf/railsystem.pdf |archive-date=February 10, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://trimet.org/ride/stop.html?stop_id=8334 |title=Stop ID 8334 \u2013 Pioneer Square South MAX Station |publisher=TriMet |access-date=March 18, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://trimet.org/ride/stop.html?stop_id=8383 |title=Stop ID 8383 \u2013 Pioneer Square North MAX Station |publisher=TriMet |access-date=March 18, 2020}}</ref> The stations together recorded an average 5,123 riders on weekdays in fall 2019.<ref name=\"pax-census-fall-2019\"/> From the stations, westbound trains take approximately 20{{nbsp}}minutes to reach Beaverton Transit Center and 50{{nbsp}}minutes to reach Hatfield Government Center station.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://trimet.org/schedules/w/t1100_1.pdf |title=MAX Blue Line, Weekday Westbound to Portland City Center and Hillsboro |publisher=TriMet |access-date=May 23, 2019}}</ref> Eastbound trains take approximately 35{{nbsp}}minutes to reach Portland International Airport station and 50{{nbs}}minutes to reach Cleveland Avenue station.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://trimet.org/schedules/w/t1100_0.pdf |title=MAX Blue Line, Weekday Eastbound to Portland City Center and Gresham |publisher=TriMet |access-date=May 23, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{{{cite web |url=https://trimet.org/schedules/w/t1090_0.pdf |title=MAX Red Line, Weekday To Portland City Center and Airport |publisher=TriMet |access-date=May 23, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* {{cite web |url=https://trimet.org/ride/stop.html?stop_id=8334 |title=Stop ID 8334 \u2013 Pioneer Square South MAX Station |publisher=TriMet}}\n* {{cite web |url=https://trimet.org/ride/stop.html?stop_id=8383 |title=Stop ID 8383 \u2013 Pioneer Square North MAX Station |publisher=TriMet}}\n\n{{TriMet railway stations|Blue=y|Red=y}}\n\n[[Category:1986 establishments in Oregon]]\n[[Category:MAX Blue Line]]\n[[Category:MAX Light Rail double stations]]\n[[Category:MAX Red Line]]\n[[Category:Railway stations in Portland, Oregon]]\n[[Category:Railway stations in the United States opened in 1986]]\n[[Category:Southwest Portland, Oregon]]\n", "name_user": "Truflip99", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eService:25", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pioneer_Square_South_and_Pioneer_Square_North_stations"}
{"title_page": "Hot in Cleveland (season 6)", "text_new": "{{Infobox television season\n |bgcolour     = #B10C28\n |image        = \n |caption      = \n |country      = United States\n |num_episodes = 24<ref name=\"seasonsix\"/>\n |network      = [[TV Land]]\n |first_aired  = {{Start date|2014|11|5}}\n |last_aired   = {{End date|2015|6|3}}\n |prev_season  = [[Hot in Cleveland (season 5)|Season 5]]\n |episode_list = List of Hot in Cleveland episodes\n}}\n\nThe sixth and final season of the [[TV Land]] original sitcom ''[[Hot in Cleveland]]'' premiered on November 5, 2014,<ref name=\"seasonsixpremiere\">{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2014/09/the-exes-renewed-12-episodes-season-4-829923/|title=TV Land\u2019s \u2018The Exes\u2019 Gets 12-Episode Order: Video|publisher=Deadline.com|accessdate=September 5, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"seasonsixepisodes\">{{cite web|url=http://www.zap2it.com/tv/hot-in-cleveland/episodes/SH012599310000?showtype=upcoming|title=Hot in Cleveland - Episode Guide for Season 6|publisher=Zap2it.com|accessdate=October 19, 2014}}</ref> and consisted of 24 episodes.<ref name=\"seasonsix\">{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/tv-land-renews-hot-cleveland-700579|title=TV Land Renews 'Hot in Cleveland' for Season 6|publisher=TheHollywoodReporter|accessdate=May 1, 2014}}</ref> The series stars [[Valerie Bertinelli]], [[Wendie Malick]], [[Jane Leeves]], and [[Betty White]].\n\nOn November 17, 2014, TV Land announced that this season would be the final season of ''Hot in Cleveland''.<ref name=\"finalseason\">{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2014/11/hot-in-cleveland-cancelled-six-seasons-tv-land-1201287034/|title=\u2018Hot In Cleveland\u2019 To End Run After Six Seasons On TV Land|publisher=Deadline.com|date=November 17, 2014|accessdate=November 17, 2014}}</ref> The series concluded June 3, 2015 after six seasons and 128 episodes. The two-part series finale (Vegas Baby; I Hate Goodbyes) aired as an hour-long episode.\n\n==Cast==\n{{Col-begin}}\n{{Col-break}}\n\n===Main===\n* [[Valerie Bertinelli]] as Melanie Moretti\n* [[Jane Leeves]] as Rejoyla \"Joy\" Scroggs\n* [[Wendie Malick]] as Victoria Chase\n* [[Betty White]] as Elka Ostrovsky\n\n===Recurring===\n* [[Georgia Engel]] as Mamie Sue Johnson\n* [[Dave Foley]] as Bob\n* [[Craig Ferguson]] as Simon\n* [[Rhys Darby]] as Jack\n* [[Michael McMillian]] as Owen\n* [[William Baldwin]] as Dane\n\n===Special guest stars===\n* [[Mario Lopez]] as himself\n* [[Robert Wagner]] as Jim\n* [[Ben Vereen]] as Mayor Deacon\n* [[Ernie Hudson]] as himself\n* [[Stacy Keach]] as Alex Chase\n* [[Missi Pyle]] as Canadian Joy\n* [[Mackenzie Phillips]] as Kaylin\n* [[Gladys Knight]] as Miss Shonda\n* [[Garry Marshall]] as Ari\n* [[George Takei]] as Reverend Matsuda\n* [[Marla Gibbs]] as Marcia\n* [[Carol Burnett]] as Penny Chase\n* [[Chris Colfer]] as Tony Chase\n* [[Juliet Mills]] as Philipa Scroggs\n* [[Huey Lewis]] as Johnny Revere\n* [[Thomas Gibson]] as Tom\n* [[Bob Newhart]] as Bob Sr.\n\n{{Col-break}}\n\n===Guest stars===\n* [[Tom Parker (actor)|Tom Parker]] as Peter\n* [[Timm Sharp]] as Zed\n* [[Andrew J. West]] as Cooper\n* [[Will Sasso]] as Frankie\n* [[Bryce Johnson]] as Dylan\n* [[Millicent Martin]] as Agnes\n* Bayne Gibby as Mona\n* [[Lesley Nicol (actress)|Lesley Nicol]] as Margaret\n* Kelly Schumann as Sally\n* Samantha Martin as Jenna\n* [[Adam Korson]] as Barney\n* [[Sophie Winkleman]] as Jill Scroggs\n* [[Adam Croasdell]] as Earl of Cleveland\n* [[Sunkrish Bala]] as Anderson\n* [[Adam Korson]] as Barney\n* [[Artemis Pebdani]] as Miss O'Roarke\n* [[Brian Baumgartner]] as Claude\n* [[Nick Searcy]] as Chief Barker\n* [[Amber Valletta]] as Ashley\n* [[Timothy Omundson]] as Mark\n* [[Andy Milder]] as Dr. Laird\n* [[Ray Abruzzo]] as Phil\n* [[Matt Walsh (comedian)|Matt Walsh]] as Arnie\n* [[Kurt Fuller]] as Gerald\n* [[Kelen Coleman]] as Andie\n* [[Yvette Nicole Brown]] as Lily\n* [[Jenny O'Hara]] as Helen\n* [[Dennis Haskins]] as Reverend Bower\n* [[Jim O'Heir]] as Ross\n* [[Marla Sokoloff]] as Chloe\n* [[Tate Ellington]] as Kameron\n* [[Todd Grinnell]] as Nicky\n* [[Tyler Ritter]] as Bart\n* [[Darlene Hunt]] as Phyllis\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Production==\nOn May 1, 2014, TV Land renewed ''Hot in Cleveland'' for a sixth season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2014/05/01/hot-in-cleveland-renewed-for-season-six-by-tv-land/259673/ |title=\u2018Hot In Cleveland\u2019 Renewed for Season Six by TV Land - Ratings |publisher=TVbytheNumbers.Zap2it.com |date=2014-05-01 |accessdate=2014-08-18}}</ref> Taping for season six began on September 19, 2014,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/hotnclevelandtv/status/513113424814166017 |title=Twitter / Hot in Cleveland: 10 mins til show time! |publisher=Twitter |date=September 19, 2014 |accessdate=October 19, 2014}}</ref> and concluded on April 2, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/thethrillionair/status/583852016197361664 |title=Twitter / Tony Stengal: On Set \"Hot In Cleveland\" Series finale! |publisher=Twitter |date=April 2, 2015 |accessdate=April 23, 2015}}</ref> On November 17, 2014, TV Land announced that season six would be the final season.<ref name=\"finalseason\"/> Guest stars for this season include: [[Ernie Hudson]] as one of Victoria's ex-husbands who helps her come to terms with their once embarrassing legacy, [[Andrew J. West]] as a young man that hits on Melanie, [[Timm Sharp]] as the producer of Victoria's new TV show, and [[Robert Wagner]] as Jim, a new man in Elka's life. [[Mario Lopez]] also made an appearance as himself. [[Sophie Winkleman]] guest stars as Joy's sister, Jill. Returning guest stars for the sixth season include [[Georgia Engel]], [[Craig Ferguson]], [[Dave Foley]], [[Michael McMillian]], [[Will Sasso]], [[Brian Baumgartner]], [[Chris Colfer]] and [[Carol Burnett]]. [[Rhys Darby]] also recurred this season as Jack, a new neighbor and Melanie's brief love interest. [[William Baldwin|Billy Baldwin]] appears in a story arc as Dane Stevens, a reporter who becomes attracted to Melanie. [[Stacy Keach]] plays Victoria's father Alex in two episodes. [[Missi Pyle]] also appears in two episodes as \"Canadian Joy\", Bob's lover from his home country whom he almost marries. [[Ben Vereen]] appears as the Mayor of Cleveland. [[Kelen Coleman]] portrays Andi, Owen's bride-to-be, while [[George Takei]] makes an appearance as the priest for their ceremony. [[Bob Newhart]] and [[Thomas Gibson]] guest-starred in the series finale, while [[Huey Lewis]] reprised his role as Johnny Revere in this same episode.\n\n==Release==\nSeason six was released in [[DVD region codes|Region 1]] on April 26, 2016. The DVD includes all 24 episodes on 3 discs.\n\n==Episodes==\n{{main|List of Hot in Cleveland episodes}}\n<onlyinclude>{{Episode table |background=#B10C28|overall=4 |season=4 |title= |director=17 |writer=20 |airdate=16 |prodcode=7 |country= U.S. |viewers=10  |episodes=\n\n{{Episode list/sublist|Hot in Cleveland (season 6)\n| EpisodeNumber   = 105\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 1\n| Title           = Comfort and Joy\n| DirectedBy      = [[John Whitesell]]\n| WrittenBy       = [[Rachel Sweet]]\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2014|11|5}}\n| ProdCode        = 601\n| Viewers         = 0.66<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.showbuzzdaily.com/articles/showbuzzdailys-top-25-wednesday-cable-originals-11-5-2014.html|title= Top 25 Wednesday Cable Originals (& Network Update): 11.5.2014|work=ShowBuzzDaily|date=November 5, 2014|accessdate=November 7, 2014}}</ref>\n| ShortSummary    = Joy announces to the girls that she wants to marry Simon, but not before she first informs Mitch and Detective Bob. Mitch finds out immediately, as he had bugged the house, while Melanie takes the task of telling Bob, only to end up sleeping with him after. Joy tells Simon \"yes\" and he is thrilled, but the moment is spoiled when Simon introduces his current 23-year-old wife to Joy. Simon explains he had to marry the woman to get her out of a dangerous situation in her home country, but vows to divorce her as soon as it is safe. When circumstances call for Simon to leave the country again, Joy realizes they shouldn't be together. Bob tries to swoop in and propose to Joy, but she says she is not looking to marry anyone at the moment. Nonetheless, Bob says he will keep trying, announcing that he's bought back the detective agency from Mitch. Elsewhere, Victoria enlists Susan Lucci's help in getting back an HBO series role that Helen Mirren had stolen, only to be double-crossed by Lucci.\n| LineColor       = B10C28\n}}\n{{Episode list/sublist|Hot in Cleveland (season 6)\n| EpisodeNumber   = 106\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 2\n| Title           = Fear and Loathing in Los Angeles\n| DirectedBy      = John Whitesell\n| WrittenBy       = [[Michael A. Ross]]\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2014|11|12}}\n| ProdCode        = 602\n| Viewers         = 0.77<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvmediainsights.com/tv-ratings/wednesday-final-nationals-voice-law-order-svuchicago-pd-crossover-propels-nbc-victory/|title=Wednesday Final Nationals: 'The Voice', 'Law and Order SVU'/'Chicago PD' Crossover Propels NBC to Victory - TV Media Insights - TV Ratings & News - Network TV Show Reviews and Daily Ratings|work=TV Media Insights|date=November 13, 2014|access-date=November 14, 2014|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150124070141/http://www.tvmediainsights.com/tv-ratings/wednesday-final-nationals-voice-law-order-svuchicago-pd-crossover-propels-nbc-victory/|archive-date=January 24, 2015|df=}}</ref>\n| ShortSummary    = Victoria has to travel to L.A. to meet Zed ([[Timm Sharp]]), the quirky director of her new HBO series, and the girls all tag along. After meeting Victoria, Zed reconsiders and cuts her from the role, thinking she is not sexy enough for the [[Malibu, California|Malibu]] setting. Meanwhile, Joy tries to convince a well-known L.A.-area Private Eye that she can still be \"honey bait\" but she fails, while Melanie is hit on by a much younger man, only to discover he needs a photo with a HOG (Hot Older Gal) for a scavenger hunt. Elka fails to convince [[Mario Lopez]] to relocate his TV show to Cleveland as part of her \"Film Cleveland\" incentive, but she does convince Zed to shoot the HBO series there. While re-visualizing the series with a Cleveland backdrop, Zed decides that Victoria is now perfect for the lead.\n| LineColor       = B10C28\n}}\n{{Episode list/sublist|Hot in Cleveland (season 6)\n| EpisodeNumber   = 107\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 3\n| Title           = Bossy Cups\n| DirectedBy      = Andy Cadiff\n| WrittenBy       = Lisa Slopey\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2014|11|19}}\n| ProdCode        = 603\n| Viewers         = 0.72<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.showbuzzdaily.com/articles/showbuzzdailys-top-25-wednesday-cable-originals-11-19-2014.html|title=SHOWBUZZDAILY\u2019s Top 25 Wednesday Cable Originals (& Network Update): 11.19.2014|publisher=ShowBuzzDaily|date=November 20, 2014|accessdate=November 26, 2014}}</ref>\n| ShortSummary    = Melanie gets to know her \"He Said/She Said\" co-host, Franky, a little better while he helps her install shelves in a bedroom closet. Victoria looks to parlay her recent fame into a successful internet project and enlists Joy to be a part of it, but the producer has other ideas and brings in a British actress to play Joy's part. Elka hits on a handsome senior named Jim ([[Robert Wagner]]), but finds that his beneath-the-surface qualities aren't very exciting.\n| LineColor       = B10C28\n}}\n{{Episode list/sublist|Hot in Cleveland (season 6)\n| EpisodeNumber   = 108\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 4\n| Title           = Naked and Afraid\n| DirectedBy      = John Whitesell\n| WrittenBy       = [[Sebastian Jones (television producer)|Sebastian Jones]]\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2014|11|26}}\n| ProdCode        = 604\n| Viewers         = 0.79<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.showbuzzdaily.com/articles/showbuzzdailys-top-25-wednesday-cable-ori